##
## USING_AMIGAGUIDE
##
@node USING_AMIGAGUIDE "Rush Help -- Using AmigaGuide"
@{b}Using AmigaGuide® with Rush@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

@{b}AmigaGuide® @{ub}can be invoked from within Rush with the Help key or
selecting the @{b}AmigaGuide® @{ub}menu item under the Help menu.

Once the @{b}AmigaGuide® @{ub}window is opened, Rush's window can be activated
again and the Help key can be pressed while the mouse is over any area
of Rush's window.  @{b}AmigaGuide® @{ub}will then update to show help on this
area of Rush's window.

The Help key can also be pressed while the mouse is over a menu item
and help will be shown on that menu item.

If the Help is pressed over an area that Rush does not know about the
table of contents will be shown.

When inside any of the windows that open on Rush, it does not matter
where the mouse is when the Help key is pressed, the help will explain
the entire window.

@endnode USING_AMIGAGUIDE

##
## KEYS
##
@node KEYS "Rush Help -- Keystrokes"
@{b}Keystrokes@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

@{b}Return or Tab@{ub}
  Activates the @{"directory string gadget" link DIRSTRGAD} on the active
  side.

@{b}Up Arrow@{ub}
  Scrolls the @{"listview" link LISTVIEW} on the active side up one line.

@{b}Down Arrow@{ub}
  Scrolls the @{"listview" link LISTVIEW} on the active side down one
  line.

@{b}Shift Up Arrow@{ub}
  Scrolls the @{"listview" link LISTVIEW} on the active side up one page.

@{b}Shift Down Arrow@{ub}
  Scrolls the @{"listview" link LISTVIEW} on the active side down one
  page.

@{b}Left Arrow@{ub}
  Scrolls the @{"listview" link LISTVIEW} on the active side left one character.

@{b}Right Arrow@{ub}
  Scrolls the @{"listview" link LISTVIEW} on the active side right one character.

@{b}Shift Left Arrow@{ub}
  Scrolls the @{"listview" link LISTVIEW} on the active side left one page.

@{b}Shift Right Arrow@{ub}
  Scrolls the @{"listview" link LISTVIEW} on the active side right one page.

@{b}Delete@{ub}
  Changes the active side to the other side.

@{b}Space@{ub}
  Rereads the directory on the active side.

@{b}Ctrl-E@{ub}
  Expands the directory name on the active side into its full path.
  For example "env:rush" would expand to "Ram Disk:env/rush".

@{b}D@{ub}
  Puts up the @{"device list" link DEVICELIST} on the active side.

@{b}M@{ub}
  If the directory on the active side is a multiple assign, this will
  bring up a listview of the directories that this multiple assign
  points to, allowing any of these directories to be loaded.

  See @{"Multiple Assign" link MULTIASSIGN_REQ} window.

@{b}A@{ub}
  Toggles between ascending and descending @{"sort" link SORT}.

@{b}R@{ub}
  Toggles between directories first and directories mixed @{"sort" link SORT}.

@{b}O@{ub}
  Cycles the @{"listview" link LISTVIEW} @{"sort" link SORT} type between: name, size, date.
  Shift-O cycles backwards.

@{b}P@{ub}
  Activates the @{"pattern gadget" link PATTERN}.

@{b}ESC@{ub}
  Closes any of Rush's windows, same as press the Close Gadget.


The following keystrokes are active during @{"internal commands" link INTERNALCMDS} (copy, move,
delete, protect, and size).

@{b}Esc@{ub}
  Abort the current command.

@{b}Space@{ub}
  Pause the current command.

@endnode KEYS

##
## MOUSE
##
@node MOUSE "Rush Help -- Mouse"
@{b}Mouse@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

@{b}LeftButton@{ub}
  The left mouse button selects the side that is clicked on.  If the
  mouse is above a gadget it will execute the gadgets functions.

@{b}MiddleButton@{ub}
  The middle mouse button can execute any @{"internal command" link INTERNALCMDS}.
  The command the middle button executes can be changed using the
  @{"Miscellaneous settings window" link MENU_MISC}.  Before the command is executed
  whatever side the mouse is over is activated.

@{b}RightButton@{ub}
  The middle mouse button can execute any @{"internal command" link INTERNALCMDS}.
  The command the right button executes can be changed using the
  @{"Miscellaneous settings window" link MENU_MISC}.  Before the command is executed
  whatever side the mouse is over is activated.

See the @{"listviews" link LISTVIEW} section for more information on using the mouse in
the listviews.

@endnode MOUSE

##
## REQUESTERS
##
@node REQUESTERS "Rush Help -- Requesters"
@{b}Requesters@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

This section explains the requesters that can come up while using Rush.
When Rush is executing @{"internal commands" link INTERNALCMDS} regular DOS requesters are
disabled.  There are five different requesters, one is a general error
requester and the other four are specific to the current operation.

@{b}General Error Requester@{ub}
  The general error requester will come up for errors which you can only
  retry or cancel.  The requester will say, "Error: could not @{i}command @{ui}
  @{i}filename@{ui}" and give a reason why the error occurred.  @{i}Command @{ui}is the
  operation that failed and @{i}filename@{ui} is the file the error occurred on.

  Your choices will be:  @{b}Retry@{ub}, @{b}SkipErrors@{ub}, @{b}Skip@{ub}, and @{b}Cancel@{ub}.

      @{b}Retry@{ub} will retry the operation that failed.

      @{b}SkipErrors@{ub} will skip the operation on this file and any other
      errors that occur during this operation.  Errors that are skipped
      are added to the error list with the @{b}Skipped@{ub} column set to @{b}Yes@{ub}.
      The error list can be shown with the @{"ShowErrors" link MENU_SHOWERRORS} menu item.

      @{b}Skip@{ub} will skip the operation on this file and the error requester
      will be shown again if another error occurs.

      @{b}Cancel@{ub} will abort the current operation.

@{b}Delete Requester@{ub}
  The delete requester will come up if you have ask deletion option on.
  The requester will say, "You cannot get back what you delete!, Ok to
  delete @{i}file@{ui}?, Selected: # file(s) # dir(s)".  @{i}File@{ui}
  is the file that will be deleted.  # are the number of files and
  directories that are selected.

  Your choices will be:  @{b}Delete@{ub}, @{b}DeleteAll #@{ub}, @{b}Skip@{ub}, and @{b}Cancel@{ub}.

      @{b}Delete@{ub} will delete the file and ask again for the next file.

      @{b}DeleteAll #@{ub} will delete the file and all the following selected
      files.  # is the total number of selected files and directories,
      this is not the actual number of files that will be deleted, it
      is the number of selected files.

      @{b}Skip@{ub} will not delete the file and ask again for the next file.

      @{b}Cancel@{ub} will abort the delete operation.

  See the Delete Options in the @{"Internal Commands settings window" link MENU_INTCMDS}
  for information on setting the ask deletion option.

@{b}Protected From Deletion Requester@{ub}
  The protected from deletion requester will come up if a file is
  protected from deletion and it is trying to be deleted.  It will say,
  "Could not Delete @{i}file@{ui}, file is protected from deletion", where @{i}file@{ui}
  is the file trying to be deleted.

  Your choices will be:  @{b}Delete@{ub}, @{b}DeleteAll@{ub}, @{b}SkipProtect@{ub}, @{b}Skip@{ub},
  and @{b}Cancel@{ub}.

      @{b}Delete@{ub} will overwrite the protection bits and delete the
      file, and ask again for the next file that is protected from
      deletion.

      @{b}DeleteAllProtect #@{ub} will overwrite the protection bits and delete
      all files that are protected from deletion.  # is the total number
      of selected files and directories

      @{b}SkipProtected@{ub} will not delete this or any file that is protected
      from deletion.

      @{b}Skip@{ub} will not delete this file, and it will ask again for the next
      file that is protected form deletion.

      @{b}Cancel@{ub} will abort the delete operation.

@{b}Copy Requester@{ub}
  The copy requester will come up if you have the askover write option
  on for copy/move.  It will say, "@{i}file@{ui} already exists", and give the
  size, protection bits, date, and time of both the source and
  destination files.  @{i}File@{ui} is the file that already exists on the
  destination side.

  Your choices will be:  @{b}Replace@{ub}, @{b}ReplaceAll@{ub}, @{b}SkipAll@{ub}, @{b}Skip@{ub}, and @{b}Cancel@{ub}.

      @{b}Replace@{ub} will replace the file and ask again for the next file that
      exists.

      @{b}ReplaceAll@{ub} will replace the file and all files that exist after
      that.

      @{b}Skip@{ub} will skip the file and ask again for the next file that
      exists.

      @{b}SkipAll@{ub} will skip the file and all files that exist.

      @{b}Cancel@{ub} will abort the copy operation.

  See the Copy Options in the @{"Internal Commands settings window" link MENU_INTCMDS}
  for information on setting the askover write option.

@{b}Read, Write, and Delete Protected Requester@{ub}
  Starting with AmigaDOS 2.0 the filesystem allows files to be protected
  from reading and writing.  This requester will come up if one these files
  read or written.  It will say "Could not @{i}command file@{ui}, file is protected
  from deletion, reading, or writing".  @{i}Command @{ui}is the operation
  that failed and @{i}file@{ui} is the file that is protected from deletion,
  reading, or writing.

  Your choices will be:  @{b}OverWriteProtection@{ub}, @{b}SkipProtected@{ub}, @{b}Skip@{ub},
  @{b}Cancel@{ub}.

      @{b}OverWriteProtection@{ub} will overwrite the file and ask again for the
      next file that is protected.

      @{b}SkipProtected@{ub} will skip the file and all files that are protected.

      @{b}Skip@{ub} will skip the file and ask again for the next file that is
      protected.

      @{b}Cancel@{ub} will abort the operation.

@endnode REQUESTERS

##
## MESSAGES
##
@node MESSAGES "Rush Help -- Error Messages"
@{b}Error Messages@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

This section explains some of the messages that might be shown by
Rush.  Most of the messages are shown in a requester, but some are
shown in the @{"status area" link STATUS}.  Most of the messages are errors, but
some are just warnings or helpful information.  Below is an explanation
of each of the messages, there are three sections labeled @{i}error requester@{ui},
@{i}shell message@{ui}, or @{i}status message@{ui}.  @{i}Error requester@{ui} means an error
requester shows the error.  @{i}Shell message@{ui} means the message is printed
to the shell that Rush is run from.  @{i}Status message@{ui} means the message
is shown in the @{"status area" link STATUS}.

@{b}Error requesters@{ub}

Could not open the preference file.

There were errors in the preference file.  Run Rush from a Shell to
see the errors when they are printed.

Could not iconify Rush, Workbench might be not be opened.

Online help requires AmigaGuide

Could not CreateGadgets.

Could not Lock xxx

Error reading xxx

Could not save settings as xxx  yyy

Rush.guide file not found in the AmigaGuide path

Could not lock PublicScreen xxx.

Could not OpenScreen, xxx
  where xxx is on of the following:
    monitor not available.
    new chipset not available.
    memory not available.
    chip memory not available.
    public screen already open.
    mode ID is unknown.
    deeper than hardware supports.
    unknown error.

@{b}Shell messages@{ub}

Error: line yyy, 'xxx' is not a valid internal command

Error: xxx: line yyy: 

Error: xxx: line yyy: 'zzz' is not a valid command.\n

@{b}Status messages@{ub}

Can not archive extract to device list, select a destination directory

Can not copy or move to device list, select a destination directory

NOTE: nothing was done, pattern gadget might have an unwanted value.

There were errors, check ShowErrors to see a full description.

@endnode MESSAGES

##
## CLI_WB
##
@node CLI_WB "Rush Help -- Cli Options"
@{b}Cli Options and Workbench Tooltypes@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The Cli options and the Workbench tooltypes are the same except that the
screen type must have SCREEN= in front of it for the Workbench tooltypes.
The first six options are the screen type.

The Cli options and Workbench tooltypes overwrite the options that are
in the preference file.

WB/S                Open Rush as a window on the Workbench screen.
HIRES/S             Open on a HiRes screen.
SHR=SUPERHIRES/S    Open on a SuperHiRes screen.
PRO=PRODUCTIVITY/S  Open on a Productivity screen.
NOLACE/S            Open on a non-interlace screen.
LACE/S              Open on an interlace screen.

L=LEFT/K/N          TopEdge of Rush's window or screen
T=TOP/K/N           LeftEdge of Rush's window or screen
W=WIDTH/K/N         Width of Rush's window or screen.
H=HEIGHT/K/N        Height of Rush's window or screen.
D=DEPTH/K/N         Depth of Rush screen.
PS=PUBSCREEN/K      Open on specific pubscreen.
PREFS/K             Used to specify prefs file to use on startup.  If a
                    prefs file is specified then RUSH.PREFS will NOT
                    be read.
DISPLAYID/K         Used to specify any screen type to open.  The
                    DisplayID's are listed in C include files if
                    you have them.
ICON=STARTICONIFY/K Start Rush in the iconified state.
AREXX=MACRO/K       Execute the specified Arexx script when Rush	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
                    is started.						  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}

The following tooltypes are used by Workbench when a program is
started in the WBStartup drawer.

DONOTWAIT    Workbench will not wait for the program to finish
             before executing the next program in the drawer.
WAIT=#       The number of seconds for Workbench to wait before
             executing the next program in the drawer.
STARTPRI=#   Order Workbench will execute programs in the drawer,
             higher priority program will execute first. 

@endnode CLI_WB

##
## CONCEPTS
##
@node CONCEPTS "Rush Help -- Concepts"
@{b}Concepts unique to Rush@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

This section explains some of the ideas that are unique to Rush.

@{b}Sort Lists@{ub}
  The sort list is a list of directories with a @{"sort" link SORT} tag
  connected to each directory.  When a directory is loaded into one of
  the @{"listviews" link LISTVIEW}, the name of the directory is compared to each of the
  directories in the sort list, if the directory is found the @{"listview" link LISTVIEW}
  @{"sort" link SORT} options will be changed to the values in the sort
  list for that directory.  The directory names in the sort list can
  also include AmigaDOS wildcards.

  An example sort list might look like this:

    sortlist DIR "dh2:downloads" SORT dscend BY date WITH dirsmixed DISPLAY date
    sortlist DIR "#?"            SORT ascend BY name WITH dirsfirst DISPLAY size

  When a directory is loaded what this would do is check to see if the
  directory name is "dh2:downloads", if is was it would load that
  directory and sort it descending by date with directories and files
  mixed and displaying the date.  Since the last entry in the sort list
  is "#?", which matches any directory, if any other directory other than
  "dh2:downloads" is loaded it will be sorted ascending by name with
  directories before files and displaying the file size.

  The sort list can be changed in the @{"Listview settings window" link MENU_LISTVIEW}.

@{b}Archive Extract List, Archive List List, Double Click List@{ub}
  These three things are very similar, the only difference is what list
  gets searched.  When the archive extract @{"center gadget" link CENTERGADS} is pressed the
  @{i}archive extract@{ui} list is searched.  When the archive list @{"center gadget" link CENTERGADS}
  is pressed the @{i}archive list@{ui} list is searched.  When a file in one of
  the @{"listviews" link LISTVIEW} is double clicked on the @{i}double click@{ui} list is searched.

  Since the three lists work the same, only the the @{i}archive extract@{ui} list
  will be explained here.  The @{i}archive extract@{ui} list contains three
  fields, an extension, a pattern, and a command.  The extension is a
  string that will be compared to the selected filename, it can include
  AmigaDOS wildcards.  The pattern is a template of up to 64 bytes that
  will be compared to the contents of the selected file.  The command is
  the command that will get executed on the selected file if the
  extension and pattern match the file.  If the extension or pattern is
  blank it will be ignored, this allows only one of the two to be
  provided.

  This makes it so only one archive extract command is need, rather then
  one for each different archive type, and since the archive list is
  configurable, new archive types can be added to it.

  An example @{i}archive extract@{ui} list might look like this:
    ArchExtList EXT ""       PATTERN "??-lh?-" COMMAND "lha -M x %s"
    ArchExtList EXT "#?.tar" PATTERN ""        COMMAND "tar xvf %s"

  When archive extract is executed it first look to see if the file had
  "??-lh?-" as the first seven bytes of the file.  If it did, lha would
  be executed on the file.  If did not, the filename would be compared
  to "#?.tar", if it matched, tar would be executed on the file.
  A question mark in the pattern will match any character.

  The @{i}archive extract@{ui} list and @{i}archive list@{ui} list can be changed in the
  @{"Archive settings window" link MENU_ARCH}.

  The @{i}double click@{ui} list can be changed in the
  @{"Double Click settings window" link MENU_DCLICK}

@{b}Select List@{ub}
  The select list is a list of the selected files or directories.  This
  list contains the selected items from the @{"listviews" link LISTVIEW} and the selected
  items from directories that are not currently being displayed.  The
  idea is that items can be selected, then another directory can be
  loaded, and when the original directory is loaded again the files will
  still be selected.  When a directory is loaded and it has selected
  items, the first selected item will be visible so the user knows
  there are selected items.

@endnode CONCEPTS

##
## HINTS
##
@node HINTS "Rush Help -- Hints"
@{b}Common Problems and Helpful Hints@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

@{b}Common Problems@{ub}

 · Make sure you are running release levels of the AmigaDOS, beta
   version known to have problems.  For example v40.2 of AmigaGuide
   has a problem that will cause Rush to crash.


@{b}Helpful Hints@{ub}

 · Resident commonly used @{"external commands" link EXTERNALCMDS} and double click commands.
   This greatly increases the speed even on machines with fast
   harddisks.  An example of a commonly used program might be a reader
   program that gets executed when a text file is double clicked on.


@endnode HINTS

##
## ABOUT
##
@node ABOUT  "Rush Help -- About"
@{b}About@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

I started writing Rush on June 25 1991 and programmed it during my
senior year in college and evenings when I am not working my real job.
The ideas behind Rush are to keep is simple yet make it powerful and
flexible enough to do its job.  Another strong idea is the use the
AmigaOS as much as possible and not try to create my own 3-d look just
for AmigaDOS 1.3 compatibility.  Gadtools and boopsi are used for
gadgets, locale.library is used for localization, and AmigaGuide® is
used for online help.  Rush is not just AmigaDOS 3.0 compatible, like
some other programs, it uses all the features of 3.0 that make sense
for a directory utility.

A lot of work has gone into Rush, for example the revision number
4908, is the number of times Rush has been compiled.


@{b}About the Author:@{ub}
  I received my Bachelor of Science in Electrical Engineering from
  Northeastern University in Boston, MA in June 1992.  I have been
  programming the Amiga since 1987.

  I can be reached by email at dkeller@bix.com.

@{b}Technical specification:@{ub}
  Rush is made up of about 610k of C code and a very little assembler
  code.  Custom boopsi button class is used for the center gadgets.

@{b}Developed on the Amiga using:@{ub}
  AmigaDOS 2.0, 2.1, and 3.0 on an Amiga 3000
  AmigaTeX
  CygnusEd Professional 2.12 and 3.5
  Sas/C 5.10b, 6.3, and 6.50
  WShell 2.0
  Sas2Ced 2.25
  FindADI 37
  Enforcer, Mungwall, SegTracker, and Memoration

@{b}Thanks to:@{ub}
  Mike Sinz (CBM) for wb2cli.o and pools.lib code.  Bryce Nesbitt for
  the original Enforcer, Mike Sinz for the new Enforcer and SegTracker,
  and Ewout Walraven for the original MungWall and Carolyn Scheppner for
  the new Mungwall.  William Hawes for Memoration.  Doug Walker and
  other people at Sas for a great C compiler and for reacting quickly to
  bugs and enhancements.  Rush would not have been possible with out
  these programs.  Rush, Queensr˙che, Pearl Jam, Soundgarden, George
  Winston, and all the other music that kept me sane during hours of
  programming.

@{b}Beta testers:@{ub}
