##
## LISTVIEW
##
@node LISTVIEW "Rush Help -- Listviews"
@{b}Listviews@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The listviews are the area where the directories or the device list are
displayed.  The listview entries can be sorted by name, date, and size,
see sort gadget for more information.  The listviews display the file	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
size, date and time, and protect bits.					  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}

Each listview is also an icon drop area.  If an file icon is dropped
on one of the listviews, the directory of the file is loaded is that
listview.  If a drawer icon is dropped on one of the listviews that
directory will be loaded.

@{b}LeftButton Drag@{ub}
  This is used to select or unselect multiple entries.  If the entry
  that is clicked on is an unselected entry it will be selected as will
  all the entries that are drag across.  If the entry is selected it
  will be unselected as will all the entries that are drag across.  If
  the mouse is dragged off the top or bottom of the listview, the
  listview will scroll.  If the mouse is less then 10 pixels off the
  listview it will scroll at a slow rate, if it is greater then 10
  pixels off the listview it will scroll at a faster rate.

@{b}LeftButton SingleClick@{ub}
  Toggles between selecting and unselecting the entry under the mouse.

@{b}LeftButton DoubleClick@{ub}
  If the entry is a directory this will load the directory into the
  current listview.

  If the entry is a file this will execute an external command on the
  entry.  See the @{"Double Click settings window" link MENU_DCLICK} for information on
  setting up double click commands.

@{b}Shift LeftButton@{ub}
  If the entry is a directory, this will load the directory into the
  @{i}other@{ui} listview.

@{b}Capslock LeftButton@{ub}
  If the entry is a directory, this will load the directory into the
  current listview, with only a single click.  With this option on you
  can go in and out of directories quickly with the left and right
  buttons, if the right button is configured to be the parent command.

@{b}Right Button@{ub}
  This will execute the @{"internal command" link INTERNALCMDS} that is specified in the
  @{"Miscellaneous settings window" link MENU_MISC}.

@{b}Middle Button@{ub}
  This will execute the @{"internal command" link INTERNALCMDS} that is specified in the
  @{"Miscellaneous settings window" link MENU_MISC}.

@{b}LeftButton in one listview, then LeftButton in the other listview@{ub}
  If the entry is a directory, this will load the directory into the
  @{i}other@{ui} listview.  This is the same as @{b}Shift LeftButton@{ub}.

See the @{"keystrokes" link KEYS} section for keyboard equivalents to scrolling.

See the @{"Sort gadgets" link SORT} section for sorting options for the listview.

@endnode LISTVIEW

##
## DIRSTRGAD
##
@node DIRSTRGAD "Rush Help -- Directory String Gadget"
@{b}Directory String Gadget@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The directory string gadget is where the directory is entered that
will be displayed in the @{"listview" link LISTVIEW}.

Standard AmigaDOS wildcards can be entered for the file part of the
directory.  For example "dh0:#?.info" would display only .info files.
If a wildcard is used, it will not effect the directories that are
displayed in the @{"listview" link LISTVIEW}.

See the @{"pattern gadget" link PATTERN} section for information on AmigaDOS wildcards.

To activate the string gadget you can press @{b}Return@{ub} or @{b}Tab@{ub}.

While the string gadget is active, the following keys are active:

@{b}RightAmiga-X @{ub}
  Clears the string gadget.

@{b}RightAmiga-Q @{ub}
  Undo, puts back what was in the string gadget when it was first
  activated.

@{b}Up Arrow @{ub}
  Scroll the @{"listview" link LISTVIEW} up one line.

@{b}Down Arrow @{ub}
  Scroll the @{"listview" link LISTVIEW} down one line.

@{b}Shift Up Arrow @{ub}
  Scroll the @{"listview" link LISTVIEW} up one page.

@{b}Shift Down Arrow @{ub}
  Scroll the @{"listview" link LISTVIEW} down one page.

@endnode DIRSTRGAD

##
## MULTIASSIGN
##
@node MULTIASSIGN "Rush Help -- Multiple Assigns"
@{b}Multiple Assign Gadget@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The multiple assign gadget is only enabled when the directory in the
@{"directory string gadget" link DIRSTRGAD} is a multiple assign.  When this gadget is
pressed the @{"Multiple Assign Window" link MULTIASSIGN_REQ} will be opened.  This window has a
listview containing all the directories that the multiple assign
points to, if one of the directories is selected that directory will
be load into the @{"listview" link LISTVIEW}.

Multiple assigns can be entered in the Shell with the following command:
  1> assign fonts: sys:fonts2 sys:font1 sys:fonts

@endnode MULTIASSIGN

##
## DEVICELIST
##
@node DEVICELIST "Rush Help -- Device List"
@{b}Device List Gadget@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The device list gadget will bring up the device list in the current
@{"listview" link LISTVIEW}.  If the device list is already being shown, it will
be updated.  If a floppy disk is added or removed the device list will
also be updated.

The device list shows all the devices (disks) and all the assigns in the
system.  Devices are displayed with their volume name and percentage
full, free space, and used space.  Assigns have @{i}Assign@{ui} after them and
Multiple assigns have @{i}Multiple Assign@{ui} after them.

@endnode DEVICELIST

##
## INFO
##
@node INFO "Rush Help -- Info"
@{b}Info Text Gadget@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The Info text gadget is the text area below the @{"listviews" link LISTVIEW}.  The Info
text gadget shows the percentage full, bytes free and bytes used for the
device of the directory being shown.

The two Info text gadgets, under the left and right @{"listviews" link LISTVIEW}, update
every four seconds even when an @{"internal" link INTERNALCMDS} or an @{"external" link EXTERNALCMDS} command is
being executed.

@endnode INFO

##
## SORT
##
@node SORT "Rush Help -- Sort"
@{b}Sort Gadgets@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The Sort gadgets are the three gadgets below the @{"Info text gadgets" link INFO}.  They
control the way the directory is sorted, they do not effect the device
list which is always sorted by name.

@{b}Sort@{ub}
  The @{b}Sort@{ub} gadget is used to select which field the @{"listview" link LISTVIEW} is sorted
  by.  The choices are: name, date, or size.

@{b}A/D@{ub}
  The @{b}A/D@{ub} gadget is used to select whether the sort is ascending or
  descending.  The gadget is checked for descending.

@{b}Dir@{ub}
  The @{b}Dir@{ub} gadget is used to select whether directories should be
  displayed before files or they should be mixed with files.  The gadget
  is checked for directories before files.

@endnode SORT

##
## STATUS
##
@node STATUS "Rush Help -- Status"
@{b}Status Text Gadget@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The status text gadget is located above both listviews, just below the
titlebar.  The status area is used to display information to the user.
All the @{"internal commands" link INTERNALCMDS} display what they are doing in the
status area.

When files and directories are being selected, the status text gadget
displays the @{i}total @{ui}number of files, directories, and bytes, and the
@{i}selected @{ui}files, directories, and bytes for each @{"listview" link LISTVIEW}.

@endnode STATUS

##
## PATTERN
##
@node PATTERN "Rush Help -- Pattern"
@{b}Pattern Gadget@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The pattern is located below the @{"center gadgets" link CENTERGADS}.  It is used to select the
pattern that will be used for some of the @{"internal commands" link INTERNALCMDS}.  The
@{"internal commands" link INTERNALCMDS} that use the pattern are: All, Clear, Delete, Copy, Move,
Size, Protect, and Archive Add.

Double clicking in the Pattern String gadget will change the string gadget
to "#?".

Through out Rush where wildcards can be used, including the pattern
gadget, standard AmigaDOS wild cards can be used.  The AmigaDOS
wild card characters are:

  ?       Matches a single character.
  #       Matches the following expression 0 or more times.
  (ab|cd) Matches any one of the items separated by '|'.
  ~       Negates the following expression.  It matches all strings
          that do not match the expression (ie. ~(foo) matches all
          strings that are not exactly "foo").
  [abc]   Character class: matches any of the characters in the class.
  [~bc]   Character class: matches any of the characters not in the
          class.
  a-z     Character range (only within character classes).
  %       Matches 0 characters always (useful in "(foo|bar|%)").
  *       Synonym for "#?", not available by default in 2.0.  Available
          as an option that can be turned on.

  "Expression" in the above table means either a single character
  (ex: "#?"), or an alternation (ex: "#(ab|cd|ef)"), or a character
  class (ex: "#[a-zA-Z]").

Example: enter "#?.c" in the pattern gadget, select ALL, all the files
that end in .c will be selected in the active @{"listview" link LISTVIEW}.

Other wild card examples:

  #?.(o|gst|sym)    matches any file ending with .o, .gst, or .sym.

  ~(#?.c)           matches any file NOT ending with .c.

  #?.[ch]           matches any file ending with .c or .h.

@endnode PATTERN

##
## CENTERGADS
##
@node CENTERGADS "Rush Help -- Center Gadgets"
@{b}Center Gadgets@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The center gadgets are the gadgets down the center of the screen.  They
can be defined to execute @{"internal commands" link INTERNALCMDS}, @{"external commands" link EXTERNALCMDS}, or
load a directory.  At the bottom of the center gadgets is horizontal	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
scrollbar which is used to scroll through gadgets which are defined.	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}

Valid @{"internal commands" link INTERNALCMDS} are:

  @{"Noop" link INTERNALCMDS 18 }             @{"Makedir" link INTERNALCMDS 133 }      @{"About" link INTERNALCMDS 226 }             @{"ListviewOptions" link INTERNALCMDS 274 }
  @{"All" link INTERNALCMDS 21 }              @{"Size" link INTERNALCMDS 143 }         @{"Iconify" link INTERNALCMDS 230 }           @{"ArchiveOptions" link INTERNALCMDS 279 }
  @{"Clear" link INTERNALCMDS 25 }            @{"ArchExtract" link INTERNALCMDS 154 }  @{"Quit" link INTERNALCMDS 235 }              @{"InternalCommands" link INTERNALCMDS 284 }
  @{"Invert" link INTERNALCMDS 34 }           @{"ArchList" link INTERNALCMDS 173 }     @{"CopyDirToClip" link INTERNALCMDS 239 }     @{"Miscellaneous" link INTERNALCMDS 289 }
  @{"CmpSelected" link INTERNALCMDS 38 }      @{"ArchAdd" link INTERNALCMDS 188 }      @{"CopySelToClip" link INTERNALCMDS 244 }     @{"LoadSettings" link INTERNALCMDS 294 }
  @{"Copy" link INTERNALCMDS 46 }             @{"Parent" link INTERNALCMDS 202 }       @{"PasteDirFromClip" link INTERNALCMDS 250 }  @{"AppendSettings" link INTERNALCMDS 299 }
  @{"Rename" link INTERNALCMDS 65 }           @{"Root" link INTERNALCMDS 207 }         @{"ShowErrors" link INTERNALCMDS 255 }        @{"SaveSettings" link INTERNALCMDS 304 }
  @{"Move" link INTERNALCMDS 75 }             @{"DeviceList" link INTERNALCMDS 211 }   @{"ScreenMode" link INTERNALCMDS 260 }
  @{"Delete" link INTERNALCMDS 100 }           @{"DirReRead" link INTERNALCMDS 215 }    @{"Palette" link INTERNALCMDS 265 }
  @{"Protect" link INTERNALCMDS 116 }          @{"Info" link INTERNALCMDS 219 }         @{"EditGadgets" link INTERNALCMDS 269 }

The background and text color can be changed for each gadget in the
@{"Edit Gadgets settings window" link MENU_EDITGADS}.

See the @{"Edit Gadgets settings window" link MENU_EDITGADS} for information on setting
up the center gadgets.

@endnode CENTERGADS

##
## FIT_GADGET
##
@node FIT_GADGET "Rush Help -- Fit Gadget"
@{b}Fit Gadget@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The fit gadget is the small read only box near the bottom center of
the screen.  It is between the @{"Pattern Gadget" link PATTERN} and @{"Center Gadgets" link CENTERGADS}.

This gadget shows whether the selected files and directories will fit
on the the destination side.  Directories will need to be @{"Sized" link INTERNALCMDS 143 } for fit
to be accurate.

@endnode FIT_GADGET

#####################################################################
## MENUS
##

##
## MENU_PROJECT
##
@node MENU_PROJECT "Rush Help -- Project Menu"
@{b}Project Menu@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The Project menu is the first menu, it contains the following menu items:

  @{" About...    Amiga-? " link MENU_ABOUT}
  @{" Iconify     Amiga-I " link MENU_ICONIFY}
  @{" Quit        Amiga-Q " link MENU_QUIT}

@endnode MENU_PROJECT

##
## MENU_ABOUT
##
@node MENU_ABOUT "Rush Help -- Protect Menu -- About"
@{b}Project Menu / About@{ub} @{i}Amiga-? @{ui}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

About brings up a requester that shows how many copies of Rush are
running, the version number, and date of Rush.  It will show something
like this:

  RUSH.# release X v??.???? (%.%.92)

    where # is the #'th copy of Rush running.

    X is the release number, release 1 in this case.

    ??.???? is the version number, something like 37.4390.

    (%.%.92) is the date this version of Rush was compiled on, the
    format is (day.month.year).

The public screen name and the Arexx port name are also shown, "N/A"
for the Arexx port means Arexx is not running.

@endnode MENU_ABOUT

##
## MENU_ICONIFY
##
@node MENU_ICONIFY "Rush Help -- Project Menu -- Iconify"
@{b}Project Menu / Iconify@{ub} @{i}Amiga-I @{ui}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

This iconifies Rush down to an appicon on Workbench.  By default the
appicon is unsnapshot and will appear under the last icon on the left
side of the Workbench.

Rush will use any standard icon created with IconEdit for the appicon.
The icon will be looked for def_icon.info in a directory called Prefs
off of the directory Rush is located in, then in env:rush.  For
example if Rush is located in Work:Programs, then the icon would be
Work:Programs/Prefs/def_icon.info.

To snapshot the icon at a certain position, save the icon to ram:, put
it out on the Workbench and snapshot it where you want it.  Then copy the
icon to def_icon.info in the directory Prefs off of the directory Rush
is located in.

@endnode MENU_ICONIFY

##
## MENU_QUIT
##
@node MENU_QUIT "Rush Help -- Project Menu -- Quit"
@{b}Project Menu / Quit@{ub} @{i}Amiga-Q @{ui}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

Quit will cause Rush to quit.

@endnode MENU_QUIT

##
## MENU_EDIT
##
@node MENU_EDIT "Rush Help -- Edit Menu"
@{b}Edit Menu@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The Edit menu is the second menu, it contains the following menu items:

  @{" Copy Directory   Amiga-X " link MENU_COPYDIR}
  @{" Copy Selected    Amiga-C " link MENU_COPYSEL}
  @{" Paste Directory  Amiga-V " link MENU_PASTE}

@endnode MENU_EDIT

##
## MENU_COPYDIR
##
@node MENU_COPYDIR "Rush Help -- Edit Menu -- Copy Directory"
@{b}Edit Menu / Copy Directory@{ub} @{i}Amiga-X @{ui}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

Copy Directory will copy the directory name on the active side to the
clipboard.

@endnode MENU_COPYDIR

##
## MENU_COPYSEL
##
@node MENU_COPYSEL "Rush Help -- Edit Menu -- Copy"
@{b}Edit Menu / Copy Selected@{ub} @{i}Amiga-C @{ui}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

Copy Selected will copy the selected entries on the active side to the
clipboard.  The directory name is prepended to each entry.  Each entry
is separated by a space and quoted with double quotes.

  example:  "env:sys/font.prefs" "env:sys/input.prefs" "env:sys/sound.prefs"

@endnode MENU_COPYSEL

##
## MENU_PASTE
##
@node MENU_PASTE "Rush Help -- Edit Menu -- Paste"
@{b}Edit Menu / Paste Directory@{ub} @{i}Amiga-V @{ui}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

Paste Directory pastes from the clipboard to the active side's
@{"directory string gadget" link DIRSTRGAD}, and the directory is loaded.

@endnode MENU_PASTE

##
## MENU_HELP
##
@node MENU_HELP "Rush Help -- Help Menu"
@{b}Help Menu@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The Help menu is the third menu, it contains the following menu items:

  @{" AmigaGuide© Help... [HELP] " link MENU_AMIGAGUIDE}
  @{"   Simple Help      Amiga-H " link MENU_SIMPLEHELP}

@endnode MENU_HELP

##
## MENU_AMIGAGUIDE
##
@node MENU_AMIGAGUIDE "Rush Help -- Help -- AmigaGuide"
@{b}Help Menu / AmigaGuide© Help@{ub} @{i}[HELP] @{ui}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

AmigaGuide® help will open AmigaGuide using this help file.
The AmigaGuide® menu item will be disabled when Rush is first loaded
while AmigaGuide initializes itself.  If AmigaGuide is not available or
the Rush.guide file(this file) is not found this menu item will remain
disabled.

See @{"Using AmigaGuide® with Rush" link USING_AMIGAGUIDE} for more information on using
AmigaGuide.

@endnode MENU_AMIGAGUIDE

##
## MENU_SIMPLEHELP
##
@node MENU_SIMPLEHELP "Rush Help -- Help -- Simple Help"
@{b}Help Menu / Simple Help@{ub} @{i}Amiga-H @{ui}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

Simple help will show in the @{"status area" link STATUS} what the object under the
mouse is.

See @{"Using AmigaGuide® with Rush" link USING_AMIGAGUIDE} for more information on using
AmigaGuide.

@endnode MENU_SIMPLEHELP

##
## MENU_COMMANDS
##
@node MENU_COMMANDS "Rush Help -- Commands Menu"
@{b}Commands Menu@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The Commands menu is the forth menu, it contains the following menu
item:

  @{"   Auto Icon Select Amiga-U " link MENU_AUTOICONSEL}
  @{" ShowErrors...      Amiga-O " link MENU_SHOWERRORS}

@endnode MENU_COMMANDS

##
## MENU_AUTOICONSEL
##
@node MENU_AUTOICONSEL "Rush Help -- Commands Menu -- Auto Icon Select"
@{b}Command Menu / Auto Icon Select@{ub} @{i}Amiga-U @{ui}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

Auto Icon Select is used to automatically select icons when files are
selected.  When this option is on icons and their parent file will be
selected and unselected together.

Also see @{"Auto Icon Rename" link MENU_INTCMDS 79} in the @{"Internal Commands settings window" link MENU_INTCMDS}.

@endnode MENU_COMMANDS

##
## MENU_SHOWERRORS
##
@node MENU_SHOWERRORS "Rush Help -- Commands Menu -- ShowErrors"
@{b}Command Menu / ShowErrors@{ub} @{i}Amiga-O @{ui}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

ShowErrors will open a window and show all AmigaDOS errors that have
occurred in Rush for this session.  This menu item will be disabled if
there are no errors to display.

When ever Rush brings up one of the error @{"requesters" link REQUESTERS} it adds the
filename to the error list.  A maximum of 50 errors will be shown in
this window, if more then 50 error occur, only the most recent 50 will
be seen.

The ShowErrors window has a read only listview that displays for each
error: @{b}filename@{ub}, @{b}command@{ub}, @{b}skip@{ub}, and @{b}error message@{ub}.

@{b}Filename@{ub}
  The filename is the file that the error occurred on.

@{b}Command@{ub}
  The command is the @{"internal commands" link INTERNALCMDS} that caused the error.

@{b}Skip@{ub}
  Skipped shows if the error was skipped or shown.  If skipped is @{i}yes@{ui}
  it means SkipErrors was selected on the error requester and a
  requester was not shown for the error.  If skipped is @{i}no@{ui} it means the
  error requester was shown for the error.

@{b}Error Message@{ub}
  Error message is the error message that AmigaDOS reported was the problem.

Below the listview are two gadgets, @{b}Continue@{ub} and @{b}Clear Errors@{ub}.

@{b}Continue@{ub} 
  Continue will close the ShowErrors window.

@{b}Clear Errors@{ub}
  Clear Errors will clear the error list and close the ShowErrors window.

See @{"requesters" link REQUESTERS} section for a description of the requesters that
can come up while using Rush.

@endnode MENU_SHOWERRORS

##
## MENU_AREXX
##
@node MENU_AREXX "Rush Help -- Arexx Menu "
@{b}Arexx Menu@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The Arexxs menu is the fifth menu, it contains the following menu items:

  @{" Command Shell...        Amiga-Z " link MENU_COMMAND_SHELL}
  @{" Execute Arexx Script... Amiga-Y " link MENU_EXECUTE_AREXX}

@endnode MENU_AREXX

##
## MENU_COMMAND_SHELL
##
@node MENU_COMMAND_SHELL "Rush Help -- Arexx Menu "
@{b}Arexx Menu / Command Shell@{ub} @{i}Amiga-Z @{ui}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The Command Shell is used to interactively execute Rush's @{"Arexx" link AREXX}
commands.

Return or Control-\ will close the Command Shell.

@endnode MENU_COMMAND_SHELL

##
## MENU_EXECUTE_AREXX
##
@node MENU_EXECUTE_AREXX "Rush Help -- Arexx Menu "
@{b}Arexx Menu / Execute Arexx Script@{ub} @{i}Amiga-Y @{ui}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

Execute Arexx script will open a file requester which is used to
select an Arexx script to execute.

The Arexx script will have a default host which is the same as the
copy of Rush that executed the script.  For example if two copies of
Rush are running and the second one execute a script, it will have a
default host of "RUSH.2".

@endnode MENU_EXECUTE_AREXX

##
## MENU_SETTINGS
##
@node MENU_SETTINGS "Rush Help -- Settings Menu "
@{b}Settings Menu@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The Settings menu is the sixth menu, it contains the following menu items:

  @{" Screen Mode...        Amiga-S " link MENU_SCREENMODE}
  @{" Palette...            Amiga-P " link MENU_PALETTE}
  @{" Edit Gadgets...       Amiga-G " link MENU_EDITGADS}
  @{" Listview...           Amiga-L " link MENU_LISTVIEW}
  @{" Archive...            Amiga-A " link MENU_ARCH}
  @{" Double Click...       Amiga-D " link MENU_DCLICK}
  @{" Internal Commands...  Amiga-N " link MENU_INTCMDS}
  @{" External Commands...  Amiga-E " link MENU_EXTCMDS}
  @{" Miscellaneous...      Amiga-M " link MENU_MISC}
  @{" Append Settings...    Amiga-T " link MENU_APPENDSET}
  @{" Load Settings...      Amiga-R " link MENU_LOADSET}
  @{" Save Settings...      Amiga-W " link MENU_SAVESET}

@endnode MENU_SETTINGS

##
## MENU_SCREENMODE
##
@node MENU_SCREENMODE "Rush Help -- Settings Menu -- Screen"
@{b}Settings Menu / Screen Mode@{ub} @{i}Amiga-S @{ui}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The Screen Mode settings window is used to selected the type and
size of the screen for Rush.

@{b}Display Mode@{ub}
  The listview on the left is used to select the display mode.  The
  display modes that are shown are based on the monitors in the
  Workbench monitor's drawer and the modes supported by the hardware.

@{b}Colors@{ub}
  Below the display mode listview is the Colors slider.  This is used
  to select the number of colors for the screen.

@{b}Overscan@{ub}
  Below the colors gadget is a cycle gadget used to select the overscan
  type.  The choices are @{i}Text Size@{ui} and @{i}Graphics Size@{ui}.  These correspond
  to the overscan sizes set for the current monitor in the Workbench
  overscan preference editor.  If any of the size string gadgets are
  set to @{i}default@{ui} they will change when the overscan type is changed.

@{b}Workbench@{ub}
  Below the overscan gadget a check box gadget labeled @{i}Workbench@{ui}.  If
  this gadget is selected Rush will open as a window on Workbench, if
  it is unselected Rush will open as a public screen.  When the @{i}Workbench@{ui}
  gadget is selected the @{i}Display Mode@{ui} listview, @{i}Colors@{ui} slider, and
  @{i}Overscan@{ui} type are disabled.

@{b}Left, Top, Width, Height@{ub}
  The four string gadgets on right are used to specify the Left, Top,
  Width, and Height of Rush.  If Rush is a window, on a public screen
  or Workbench, these values specify the size and position of the
  window.  If Rush is opened on its own screen these values specify
  the size and position of the screen.

@{b}Default@{ub}
  Next to each string gadget is a check box gadget labeled @{i}default@{ui}.
  When this gadget is selected the string gadget is disabled and the
  default size for the current display mode is used, otherwise a
  custom size can be entered in the string gadget.

@{b}Screen Font, Size, and Font Requester@{ub}
  The @{i}screen font@{ui} string gadget is used to enter name of the font
  which will be used for the screen.  The @{i}size@{ui} string gadget is used
  to enter the size of the font.  If the @{i}font requester@{ui} gadget is
  pressed the ASL font requester will be opened to select the listview
  font and size.  The font name and size will be displayed in the two
  string gadgets if a font is selected with the ASL font requester.  The
  @{i}font name@{ui} should include the .font extension.  If the font does not
  end with .font, .font will be added to the font name.

See the @{"arexx" link AREXX} section for a description of Arexx commands that effect	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
the screen mode.										  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}

@endnode MENU_SCREENMODE

##
## MENU_PALETTE
##
@node MENU_PALETTE "Rush Help -- Settings Menu -- Palette"
@{b}Settings Menu / Palette@{ub} @{i}Amiga-P @{ui}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The Palette window is used to change the screen colors and pens.

Across the top is a Palette gadget that is used to select the color
to change.

@{b}Red, Green, Blue@{ub}
  Below the Palette gadget are three sliders used to change the Red,
  Green, and Blue levels of the currently selected color.

@{b}Screen Pens@{ub}
  Below the color sliders are a three gadget used to change the screen
  pens.  The @{i}Default@{ui} checkbox gadget is used to select between the
  default screen pens and a custom set of screen pens.  When @{i}Default@{ui}
  is checked, the two other gadgets are disabled and the default screen
  pens will be used.  The cycle gadget is used to select which pen is
  being shown.  The button below cycle gadget, labeled @{i}Palette
  Requester...@{ui}, shows the color of the current screen pen and if
  selected it will bring up a small @{"palette window" link MIN_PALETTE} which can be
  used to select the color.

@{b}Color Wheel and Gradient Slider@{ub}
  If Rush is being run under AmigaDOS 3.0, on the right of the palette
  window will be a ColorWheel and Gradient slider gadget.  If Rush's
  screen is two, four, or eight colors the ColorWheel gadget will be
  monochrome and use letters for the different color areas.  The letter
  is the first letter of the color; R=Red, Y=Yellow, G=Green, C=Cyan,
  B=Blue, and M=Magenta.

If Rush is opened as a window on Workbench or a public screen the
color sliders and screen pen gadgets will be disabled.

See the @{"arexx" link AREXX} section for a description of Arexx commands that effect	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
the palette.										  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}

@endnode MENU_PALETTE

##
## MENU_EDITGADS
##
@node MENU_EDITGADS "Rush Help -- Settings Menu -- EditGadgets"
@{b}Settings Menu / Edit Gadgets@{ub} @{i}Amiga-G @{ui}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The Edit Gadgets window is used to change the @{"center gadgets" link CENTERGADS}.

@{b}CenterGadgets@{ub}
  The listview on the left contains the name for each @{"center gadgets" link CENTERGADS}.
  When an entry in the listview is selected the other gadgets in the
  window update to show what that entry does.

  Below the listview are five gadgets: a string gadget, @{i}add,@{ui} @{i}del,@{ui}
  @{i}plus(+),@{ui} and @{i}minus(-).@{ui}

    The string gadget shows the currently selected entry and is used to
    edit the name of the selected entry.

    The @{i}add @{ui}gadget is used to add a new entry to the listview.  The new
    entry will have a default name of "(new)".

    The @{i}del @{ui}gadget is used to delete the selected entry.

    The @{i}plus(+) @{ui}gadget is used to move the selected entry down one
    position.

    The @{i}minus(-) @{ui}gadget is used to move the selected entry up one
    position.

@{b}Gadget Type@{ub}
  In the top center are four radio buttons labeled @{i}gadget type@{ui} which are
  used the select the type of function the selected entry will perform.
  The choices are @{i}noop, internal, external,@{ui} and @{i}device.@{ui}  If @{i}noop@{ui} is
  selected the gadget will do nothing.  If @{i}internal@{ui} is selected the
  gadget will execute an @{"internal command" link INTERNALCMDS}.  If @{i}external@{ui} is selected
  the gadget will execute an external command.  If @{i}device@{ui} is selected the
  gadget will load a directory on the active side.

@{b}Gadget Color@{ub}
  Below the @{i}gadget type@{ui} radio buttons are two gadgets which are used to
  select the @{i}gadget color@{ui} of the selected entry.  One of the gadgets is
  labeled @{i}text@{ui} and one is labeled @{i}back.@{ui}  The @{i}text@{ui} gadget is used to
  change the text color of the @{"center gadget" link CENTERGADS}.  The @{i}back @{ui}gadget is used
  to select the background color of the @{"center gadget" link CENTERGADS}.  When these
  gadgets are pressed a @{"palette window" link MIN_PALETTE} will be opened for selecting
  the color for the @{"center gadget" link CENTERGADS}.

@{b}Internal Commands@{ub}
  In the upper right is a listview labeled @{i}internal commands@{ui}.  It is
  used to select the @{"internal command" link INTERNALCMDS} that will be executed when the
  @{"center gadget" link CENTERGADS} is pressed.  The @{i}internal command @{ui}listview will only be
  enabled if the @{i}gadget type@{ui} is set to @{i}internal@{ui}.

@{b}External Command@{ub}
  Below the @{i}internal command @{ui}listview is a string gadget labeled
  @{i}external command.@{ui}  This gadget is used to select an external command
  that will be executed when the @{"center gadget" link CENTERGADS} is pressed.

  A %s can be placed in the line and will be replaced with the selected
  entry from the listview when the command is executed.  A %p will be
  replaced with the public screen name of Rush.

  Also see @{"external commands" link EXTERNALCMDS} section.

  The @{i}external command @{ui}string gadget will only be enabled if the @{i}gadget
  type@{ui} is set to @{i}external@{ui}.

@{b}Device@{ub}
  Below the @{i}external command @{ui}string gadget is a string gadget labeled
  @{i}device@{ui}.  This gadget is used to select the directory that will be
  loaded on the active side when the @{"center gadget" link CENTERGADS} is pressed.  The
  @{i}device@{ui} string gadget will only be enabled if the @{i}gadget type@{ui} is set
  to @{i}device@{ui}.

@endnode MENU_EDITGADS

##
## MENU_LISTVIEW
##
@node MENU_LISTVIEW "Rush Help -- Settings Menu -- Listview"
@{b}Settings Menu / Listview@{ub} @{i}Amiga-L @{ui}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The Listview window is used to change options related to the
@{"listviews" link LISTVIEW}.

@{b}Sort List@{ub}
  The listview on the left is labeled @{i}sort list@{ui}.  It is used to enter a
  directory, including AmigaDOS wildcards, that will be sorted a specify
  way when it is loaded into one of the @{"listviews" link LISTVIEW}.

  For example if "dh0:lib#?" were in the listview, any directory
  starting with @{i}lib@{ui} on @{i}dh0:@{ui} would be sorted and displayed the way the
  @{b}Sort@{ub}, @{b}A/D@{ub}, @{b}Dir@{ub}, and @{b}Display@{ub} gadgets show.

  Also see @{"Concepts that are unique to Rush" link CONCEPTS} for a description of
  sort lists.

  Below the listview are five gadgets:  a string gadget, @{i}add,@{ui} @{i}del,@{ui}
  @{i}plus(+),@{ui} and @{i}minus(-).@{ui}

    The string gadget shows the currently selected entry and is used to
    edit the name of the selected entry.

    The @{i}add @{ui}gadget is used to add a new entry to the listview.  The new
    entry will have a default name of "(dir)".

    The @{i}del @{ui}gadget is used to delete the selected entry.

    The @{i}plus(+)@{ui} gadget is used to move the selected entry down one
    position.

    The @{i}minus(-)@{ui} gadget is used to move the selected entry up one
    position.

@{b}Sort, A/D, Dir@{ub}
  In the upper right corner are three gadgets labeled: @{i}Sort, A/D, Dir@{ui}.	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
  They are used to selected the sort and display type for the selected
  entry in the @{i}sort list@{ui} listview.

@{b}No Change@{ub}
  Below the @{i}Sort, A/D, and Dir @{ui}gadgets are checkbox gadgets		  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
  with the word @{i}No Change@{ui} next to them.  If the checkbox is checked
  the respective gadget above it will be disabled and that property
  of the @{"listview" link LISTVIEW} will @{b}not@{ub} be changed when the directory is loaded.

@{b}Listview Text Colors@{ub}
  These three gadgets are used to select the color of files,
  directories, and selected entries in the @{"listviews" link LISTVIEW}.  When these
  gadgets are pressed a @{"palette window" link MIN_PALETTE} will be opened which is used
  to select the color.

@{b}Listview Font, Size, and Font Requester@{ub}
  The @{i}listview font@{ui} string gadget is used to enter name of the font
  which will be used in the @{"listviews" link LISTVIEW}.  The @{i}size@{ui} string gadget is used
  to enter the size of the font.  If the @{i}font requester@{ui} gadget is
  pressed the ASL font requester will be opened to select the listview
  font and size.  The font name and size will be displayed in the two
  string gadgets if a font is selected with the ASL font requester.  The
  @{i}font name@{ui} should include the .font extension.  If the font does not
  end with .font, .font will be added to the font name.

See the @{"pattern gadget" link PATTERN} section for a description of AmigaDOS
wildcard patterns that can be used in the @{"sort list" link CONCEPTS 6 }.

See the @{"arexx" link AREXX} section for a description of Arexx commands that effect	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
the listviews.										  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}

@endnode MENU_LISTVIEW

##
## MENU_ARCH
##
@node MENU_ARCH "Rush Help -- Settings Menu -- Archive"
@{b}Settings Menu / Archive@{ub} @{i}Amiga-A @{ui}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The Archive window is used to change which programs are executed
for different archive types.

@{b}List@{ub}
  In the upper left corner is a cycle gadget which is labeled @{i}List@{ui},
  it is used to select which archive list is being edited: @{i}Archive
  Extract, Archive List,@{ui} or @{i}Archive Add.@{ui}

@{b}Archive Commands@{ub}
  The listview on the left is used to enter the archive command that
  will be executed if the selected file matches the @{i}Extension@{ui} or
  @{i}Type field.@{ui}

  For @{i}Archive Extract@{ui} and @{i}Archive List@{ui} a %s can be placed in the line
  and will be replaced with the selected entry from the @{"listview" link LISTVIEW} when
  the command is executed.

    example: lha x %s    or    lha v %s

  For @{i}Archive Add @{ui}a %s can be placed in the line and will be replaced
  with the new archive name the user enters when the archive command is
  executed.  A %f can be used and will be replaced with input filename
  if the @{i}Add Input Source@{ui} is set to @{i}File.@{ui}  Also see @{b}Add Input Source@{ub}
  below.

    example: lha -i%f a %s

  For @{i}Archive Extract, List,@{ui} and @{i}Add @{ui}a %p can be used and will be
  replaced with the public screen name of Rush.  A %d can be used and
  will be replaced with the destination directory name.

  Archive Add and Archive List commands are executed from the directory
  where Rush is located, this allows commands to be found relative to
  Rush's program directory.  Archive Extract commands are executed from
  the destination directory, this is so the archive extract command will
  extract its file to the destination directory.

  For example "scripts/format_disk" could be used to execute the script
  "format_disk" in a directory called "scripts" off of the directory
  where Rush is located.

  Below the listview are five gadgets: a string gadget, @{i}add,@{ui} @{i}del,@{ui}
  @{i}plus(+),@{ui} and @{i}minus(-).@{ui}

    The string gadget shows the currently selected entry and is used to
    edit the name of the selected entry.

    The @{i}add @{ui}gadget is used to add a new entry to the listview.  The new
    entry will have a default name of "cmd x %s" if adding to the extract
    list, "cmd v %s" if the adding to the list list, and "cmd a %s" if
    adding to the add list.  This is a little reminder of the command
    format.

    The @{i}del @{ui}gadget is used to delete the selected entry.

    The @{i}plus(+)@{ui} gadget is used to move the selected entry down one
    position.

    The @{i}minus(-)@{ui} gadget is used to move the selected entry up one
    position.

@{b}Extension and Type@{ub}
  The @{i}Extension@{ui} and @{i}Type@{ui} are used for @{i}Archive Extract@{ui} and @{i}Archive List@{ui}
  to find the correct archive program to extract or list the file.  The
  @{i}Extension@{ui} and @{i}Type@{ui} must both match for that archive program to be
  used.  If either the @{i}Extension@{ui} or @{i}Type@{ui} are blank it will match
  anything, for the @{i}Extension@{ui} it is the same as "#?" and for the @{i}Type@{ui} it
  is the same as "?".  If only the @{i}Extension@{ui} is to be used the @{i}Type@{ui}
  should be left blank, if only the @{i}Type@{ui} is to be used the @{i}Extension@{ui}
  should be left blank.

@{b}Extension@{ub}
  The @{i}Extension@{ui} string gadget is used to enter the extension, which can
  include AmigaDOS wildcards.

    example: #?.(lha|lzh)

@{b}Type@{ub}
  The @{i}Type@{ui} string gadget is used to entry the type of the file.  This is
  up to the first 64 bytes of the file.  A "?" can be used to match any
  character and non ASCII characters can be entered in octal format if
  escaped by a "\".  For example character 27 would be \033.  It is
  best to only use the Type field and leave the Extension blank, this
  way if an archive gets renamed the archive commands will still work.
  Also see @{b}Sample Files@{ub} below.

    example: ??-lh?-    will match lharc files.

@{b}Sample Files@{ub}
  The @{i}Sample Files@{ui} gadget will open an ASL multiselect file requester,
  which is used to select sample files of the current type.  Shift must
  be held down to select multiple files in the ASL file requester.
  These sample files will be used to fill in the @{i}Type@{ui} string gadget with
  a type that will work for the sample files.  Since the sample files
  are used to fill in the @{i}Type@{ui} string gadget, the more sample files that
  are selected the better.

  The @{i}Type@{ui} string gadget is usually filled in with more then is
  necessary and can be edited after @{i}Sample Files@{ui} is used.  For example
  the @{i}Type@{ui} string gadget might be filled in with "??-lh?-??\000\000",
  this can be edited to "??-lh?-".

@{b}Add Input Source@{ub}
  @{i}Add Input Source@{ui} cycle gadget is used to select where the Archive Add
  program gets its file list from, it can set to: @{i}File, Command Line, @{ui}or
  @{i}Standard Input.@{ui}  This gadget will only be enabled when the @{i}List@{ui}
  cycle gadget is set to Archive Add.

  When @{i}File@{ui} is used, a temporary file is created in t:.  The temporary
  file will contain a list of files to be added to the archive, with one
  filename per line.  %f should be used somewhere in the Archive Command
  line so the file list is used.

    example: lha -x -i%f a %s

  When @{i}Command Line@{ui} is used, a string up to 255 characters is build of the
  files to be added to the archive and the Archive Add program is run.
  This happens over and over again until all the files are added to the
  archive.  The drawback to this method is that Archive Add program is
  run over and over which can be slow on a floppy based system, but some
  archive commands, like Arc, only accept filenames on the command line.

    example: arc a %s

  When @{i}Standard Input@{ui} is used, a temporary file is created in t:.  Then
  temporary file will contain a list of files to be added to the archive,
  with one file per line.  This file is then redirect into standard input
  when the Archive Add program is run.

    example: zoo aI %s

  @{i}File@{ui} or @{i}Standard Input@{ui} should be used if possible since the Archive
  Add program is only run once.

@{b}Quote@{ub}
  If the @{i}Quote@{ui} checkbox is checked the filenames will be quoted with
  double quotes.  This is necessary in some cases so filenames with spaces
  can be added to the archive.

  Lha, lharc, and arc should all have Quote on, zoo should have not have
  Quote on.

@{b}Setups for Currently Available Archivers@{ub}
  Currently the following archivers are available: lharc, lha, lz, zoo,
  arc, pkax, unzip, unarj, tar, gzip, uudecode, and uncompress.  The
  following table shows suitable values for each archiver.

                       @{b}Archive Extract@{ub}
             Archive Command    Extension    Type
             ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ    ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ    ŻŻŻŻ
             lharc x %s                      ??-lh?-
             lha x %s                        ??-lh?-
             lz x %s                         ??-lh?-
             zoo x %s                        ZOO ?.?? Archive
             arc x %s           #?.arc       \032\010
             pkax -x %s         #?.arc       \032\010
             unzip %s                        PK\003\004
             unarj x %s         #?.arj
             tar xvf %s         #?.tar
             gzip %s            #?.gz        \037
             uudecode %s                     begin ???
             uncompress %s                   \037\235\220

                       @{b}Archive List@{ub}
             Archive Command    Extension    Type
             ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ    ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ    ŻŻŻŻ
             lharc v %s                      ??-lh?-
             lha v %s                        ??-lh?-
             lz v %s                         ??-lh?-
             zoo v %s                        ZOO ?.?? Archive
             arc v %s           #?.arc       \032\010
             pkax -v %s         #?.arc       \032\010
             unzip -v %                      PK\003\004
             unarj l %s         #?.arj
             tar tvf %s         #?.tar

                       @{b}Archive Add@{ub}
             Archive Command        Input Source    Quote
             ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ        ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ    ŻŻŻŻŻ
             lharc -x -i%f a %s     File            Yes
             lha -x -i%f a %s       File            Yes
             lz -x -i%f a %s        File            Yes
             zoo ahI %s             StdIn           No
             arc a %s               CmdLine         Yes
             tar cvf %s -T %f       File            No


Also see @{"Concepts that are unique to Rush" link CONCEPTS} for a description of archive
extract and archive list lists.

See the @{"External Commands setting window" link AREXX} section for a description	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
console strings which are used for the Archive commands.		  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}

The console window used for the archive commands can be changed in the
@{"External Commands settings window " link MENU_EXTCMDS}.

@endnode MENU_ARCH

##
## MENU_DCLICK
##
@node MENU_DCLICK "Rush Help -- Settings Menu -- DoubleClick"
@{b}Settings Menu / Double Click@{ub} @{i}Amiga-D @{ui}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The Double Click window is used to change which programs are
executed when a file is double clicked on.

@{b}Double Click Commands@{ub}
  The listview on the left is used to enter the command that will be
  executed if the selected file matches the @{i}Extension@{ui} or @{i}Type
  field.@{ui}

  A %s can be placed in the line and will be replaced with the selected
  entry from the @{"listview" link LISTVIEW} when the command is executed.  A %p can be
  used and will be replaced with the public screen name of Rush.  A %d
  can be used and will be replaced with the destination directory.

    example: read %s pubscreen %p

  Double Click commands are executed from the directory where Rush is
  located, this allows commands to be found relative to Rush's
  program directory.

  For example "scripts/format_disk" could be used to execute the script
  "format_disk" in a directory called "scripts" off of the directory
  where Rush is located.

  Below the listview are five gadgets: a string gadget, @{i}add,@{ui} @{i}del,@{ui}
  @{i}plus(+),@{ui} and @{i}minus(-).@{ui}

   The string gadget shows the currently selected entry and is used to
   edit the name of the selected entry.

   The @{i}add @{ui}gadget is used to add a new entry to the listview.  The new
   entry will have a default name of "cmd %s", this is a reminder of
   the command format.

   The @{i}del @{ui}gadget is used to delete the selected entry.

   The @{i}plus(+)@{ui} gadget is used to move the selected entry down one
   position.

   The @{i}minus(-)@{ui} gadget is used to move the selected entry up one
   position.

@{b}Extension and Type@{ub}
  The @{i}Extension@{ui} and @{i}Type@{ui} are used to find the correct program to
  execute when a given file is double clicked on.  The @{i}Extension@{ui} and
  @{i}Type@{ui} must both match for that program to be used.  If either the
  @{i}Extension@{ui} or @{i}Type@{ui} are blank it will match anything, for
  the @{i}Extension@{ui} it is the same as "#?" and for the @{i}Type@{ui} it is the
  same as "?".  If only the @{i}Extension@{ui}is to be used the @{i}Type@{ui} should
  be left blank, if only the @{i}Type@{ui} is to be used the @{i}Extension@{ui}
  should be left blank.

@{b}Extension@{ub}
  The @{i}Extension@{ui} string gadget is used to enter the extension, which can
  include AmigaDOS wildcards.

    example: #?.[ch]    will match any .c or .h files.

@{b}Type@{ub}
  The @{i}Type@{ui} string gadget is used to entry the type of the file.  This is
  up to the first 64 bytes of the file.  A "?" can be used to match any
  character and non ASCII characters can be entered in octal format if
  escaped by a "\".  For example character 27 would be \033.  Also see
  @{b}Sample Files@{ub} below.

    example: ??-lh?-    will match lharc files.

@{b}Sample Files@{ub}
  The @{i}Sample Files@{ui} gadget will open an ASL multiselect file requester,
  which is used to select sample files of the current type.  Shift must
  be held down to select multiple files in the ASL file requester.
  These sample files will be used to fill in the @{i}Type@{ui} string gadget with
  a type that will work for the sample files.  Since the sample files
  are used to fill in the @{i}Type@{ui} string gadget, the more sample files that
  are selected the better.

  The @{i}Type@{ui} string gadget is usually filled in with more then is
  necessary and can be edited after @{i}Sample Files@{ui} is used.  For example
  the @{i}Type@{ui} string gadget might be filled in with "??-lh?-??\000\000",
  this can be edited to "??-lh?-".

Also see @{"Concepts that are unique to Rush" link CONCEPTS} for a description of double
click lists.

See the @{"External Commands setting window" link AREXX} section for a description	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
console strings which are used for the Double Click commands.		  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}

The console window used for double click commands can be changed in
the @{"External Commands settings window " link MENU_EXTCMDS}.

@endnode MENU_DCLICK

##
## MENU_INTCMDS
##
@node MENU_INTCMDS "Rush Help -- Settings Menu -- Internal Commands"
@{b}Settings Menu / Internal Commands@{ub} @{i}Amiga-N @{ui}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The Internal commands window is used to change options for the
@{"internal commands" link INTERNALCMDS}.

@{b}Copy and Move Options@{ub}
  The Copy and Move Options are options that effect both the @{"Copy" link INTERNALCMDS 46 } and
  @{"Move" link INTERNALCMDS 75 } @{"internal commands" link INTERNALCMDS}.

  Clone Protection  - Set the protection bits on the destination file
                      the same as the source file.  If this option is
                      off the destination file will have protection
                      bits set to RWED.

  Clone Date        - Set the date of the destination file the same as
                      the source file.  If this option is off the
                      destination file's date will be set to the
                      current time.

  Clone Comment     - Set the comment of the destination file the same
                      as the source file.  If this option is off the
                      destination file will have no comment.

  Ask Overwrite     - Ask the user about overwriting files if the file
                      already exists.  See the @{"Requesters" link REQUESTERS}
                      section for information on the copy requester.

  Unset Archive Bit - Remove the archive bit of the destination file
                      when it is copied.

  The copy and move options can also be changed by holding down shift
  when the copy or move @{"center gadget" link CENTERGADS} is pressed.

@{b}Delete Options@{ub}
  The Delete Options are options that effect the @{"Delete" link INTERNALCMDS 100 }
  @{"internal command" link INTERNALCMDS}.

  Confirm Delete - Ask the user before deleting files. See the
                   @{"Requesters" link REQUESTERS} section for information
                   on the delete requester.

  The delete options can also be changed by holding down shift when the
  delete @{"center gadget" link CENTERGADS} is pressed.

@{b}Makedir Options@{ub}
  The Makedir Options are options that effect the @{"Makedir" link INTERNALCMDS 133 }
  @{"internal command" link INTERNALCMDS}.

  Create Icons - Create icons when directories are created.  The drawer
                 icon will be the default system drawer icon.

  The @{"makedir window" link MAKEDIR_REQ} also allows the Create Icons option to be
  changed when creating directories.

@{b}Protect Options@{ub}
  The Protect Options are the protection bits that will be used when
  @{"Protect" link INTERNALCMDS 116 } @{"internal command" link INTERNALCMDS} is used.

  H bit      - The H bit is currently not used by AmigaDOS.

  Script     - Set the script bit.

  Pure       - Set the pure bit.

  Archived   - Set the archived bit.

  Readable   - Set the readable bit.

  Writable   - Set the writable bit.

  Executable - Set the executable bit.

  Deletable  - Set the deletable bit.

  The protect options can also be changed by holding down shift when the
  protect @{"center gadget" link CENTERGADS} is pressed.

@{b}Rename Options@{ub}
  The Rename Options are options that effect the @{"Rename" link INTERNALCMDS 65 }
  @{"internal command" link INTERNALCMDS}.

  Auto Icon Rename - If the Auto Icon Rename checkbox is check and an
                     icon exists for the entry being renamed, the icon
                     will also be rename.  If an icon is renamed its
                     parent file or directory will also be renamed.

  The @{"rename window" link RENAME_REQ} also allows the Auto Icon Rename option to be
  changed when renaming entries.

@endnode MENU_INTCMDS

##
## MENU_EXTCMDS
##
@node MENU_EXTCMDS "Rush Help -- Settings Menu -- External Commands"
@{b}Settings Menu / External Commands@{ub} @{i}Amiga-E @{ui}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The External commands window is used to change the console strings
which are used for console windows for all AmigaDOS commands.  AmigaDOS
commands include external commands, double click commands, and archive
commands.  Each one of theses console strings can be set individually.    @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}

The console strings can contain two escape sequences, %t and %p.

  %t will be replaced with a title for the AmigaDOS command, for
     example external commands will use "External Command" for a
     title.

  %p will be replaced by the public screen name of Rush.

  Note for the Amiga Shell the SCREEN parameter must be last.

  example: con:0/200/620/200/%t/auto/close/alt0,0,640,400/screen %p

Starting with release 1.1 each type of external command can have a        @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
totally difference console string that it uses.  Unlike before when ALL   @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
external commands used the same console string, some having WAIT          @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
appended to them.                                                         @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}

@{b}External Commands@{ub}
  This is the console string which is used for @{"center gadgets" link CENTERGADS} which	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
  execute @{"external commands" link EXTERNALCMDS}.  These commands can be changed in the	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
  @{"edit gadgets settings window" link MENU_EDITGADS}.						  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}

@{b}Archive Extract@{ub}
  This is the console string which is used for Archive Extract commands.  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
  These commands can be changed using the @{"archive settings window" link MENU_ARCHIVE}.	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}

@{b}Archive List@{ub}
  This is the console string which is used for Archive List commands.	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
  These commands can be changed using the @{"archive settings window" link MENU_ARCHIVE}.	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}

  The Archive List console string should usually contain the WAIT	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
  keyword so console window says opened after the command has		  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
  executed.								  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}

@{b}Archive Add@{ub}
  This is the console string which is used for Archive Add commands.	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
  These commands can be changed using the @{"archive settings window" link MENU_ARCHIVE}.	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}

@{b}Double Click@{ub}
  This is the console string which is used for Double Click commands.	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
  These commands can be changed using the @{"double click settings window" link MENU_DCLICK}.	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}

  The Double Click console string should usually contain the WAIT	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
  keyword so console window says opened after the command has		  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
  executed.								  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}

@{b}Console@{ub}
  The Console gadget will open an example console window based on the
  contents of the @{i}Console String@{ui}.  The window can be moved and
  resize and when it is closed it will update the @{i}Console
  String@{ui} with the size.

@{b}Screen To Front@{ub}
  If this option is on, Rush's screen or window will be brought to the	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
  front after external commands are executed.				  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}

@endnode MENU_EXTCMDS

##
## MENU_MISC
##
@node MENU_MISC "Rush Help -- Settings Menu -- Misc"
@{b}Settings Menu / Miscellaneous@{ub} @{i}Amiga-M @{ui}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The Miscellaneous window is used to change which directory is
loaded when Rush is started, what the middle and right mouse
button do, and the @{"center gadget" link CENTERGADS} size.

@{b}StartUpDirLeft and StartUpDirRight@{ub}
  The two string gadgets labeled @{i}StartUpDirLeft@{ui} and @{i}StartUpDirRight@{ui} are
  used to enter a directory name that will be loaded into the left and
  right @{"listviews" link LISTVIEW} when Rush is started.

  To the right of each of the string gadgets is a drawer gadget, if this
  gadget is pressed an ASL directory requester will be opened allowing a
  directory to be selected.  The selected directory will then be
  displayed in the startup string gadget.

  To the right of each of the drawer gadgets is a checkbox gadget
  labeled @{i}Device List.@{ui} If the @{i}Device List@{ui} gadget is checked
  the device list will be shown when Rush is started instead of a
  directory.

@{b}Mouse Button Commands@{ub}
  The @{i}Mouse Button@{ui} Commands are used to select what function the middle
  and right mouse buttons will perform.  The @{i}Middle@{ui} and @{i}Right@{ui} radio
  buttons are used to select which of the two button's command is being
  show in the @{"Internal Commands" link INTERNALCMDS} listview.

  An internal command of NOOP will allow the button to perform no
  function within Rush.  For example if right button is set to NOOP is
  will be the regular menu button.  If the right button is set to
  something other then NOOP, it will still operate as the menu button
  when the mouse is in the titlebar or above it.

@{b}Gadget Size@{ub}
  @{i}Gadget Size@{ui} is used to change the size of the @{"center gadgets" link CENTERGADS}.  The
  @{i}Width@{ui}, @{i}Height@{ui},and @{i}Spacing@{ui} between the gadgets can be changed by
  using the sliders.  The valid rage for the width is between 60 and
  100 pixels.  The valid range for the height is 10 to 20 pixels and
  the valid range for the spacing is 0 to 8 pixels.

@endnode MENU_MISC

##
## MENU_APPENDSET
##
@node MENU_APPENDSET "Rush Help -- Settings Menu -- Append"
@{b}Settings Menu / Append Settings@{ub} @{i}Amiga-T @{ui}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

Append Settings is used to load a preference file.

The difference between Append Settings and @{"Load Settings" link MENU_LOADSET}, is that
@{"Load Settings" link MENU_LOADSET} will reset everything back to the defaults before loading the
preference file and Append Settings will not.

Rush's preference files are ascii text files that can be edited with a
text editor like ed.  All the options in the preference files can be
change from within Rush, but can also be changed with a text editor if
you prefer.

@endnode MENU_APPENDSET

##
## MENU_LOADSET
##
@node MENU_LOADSET "Rush Help -- Settings Menu -- Load"
@{b}Settings Menu / Load Settings@{ub} @{i}Amiga-R @{ui}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The Load Settings menu is used to load a preference file.

The difference between @{"Append Settings" link MENU_APPENDSET} and Load Settings, is that Load
Settings will reset everything back to the defaults before loading the
preference file and @{"Append Settings" link MENU_APPENDSET} will not.

Rush's preference files are ascii text files that can be edited with a
text editor like ed.  All the options in the preference files can be
change from within Rush, but can also be changed with a text editor if
you prefer.

@endnode MENU_LOADSET

##
## MENU_SAVESET
##
@node MENU_SAVESET "Rush Help -- Settings Menu -- Save"
@{b}Settings Menu / Save Settings@{ub} @{i}Amiga-W @{ui}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The Save Setting window is used to save Rush's settings to a file.

@{b}Radio Buttons@{ub}
  On the top of the Save window are four radio buttons labeled: Prefs
  and Gadgets in separate files, Prefs without Gadgets, Gadgets Only,
  Prefs and Gadgets in same file.

  @{i}Prefs@{ui} means all the single line settings, like the screen size and
  display mode.  @{i}Gadgets@{ui} means all the lists that are available in Rush,
  like Gadgets, DClickList, and others.

  @{b}Prefs and Gadgets in separate files@{ub}
    When prefs and gadgets are saved in separate files, the prefs file
    includes the gadgets file using the preference @{"include" link PREFS 400 } command.  This
    allows more then one prefs file to include the same gadgets file.  The
    reason for this is usually all prefs files will include the same
    gadgets file so only one gadgets file will have to keep up to date.

  @{b}Prefs without Gadgets@{ub}
    Prefs without gadgets will only save the prefs information without any
    @{"include" link PREFS 400 } statement.  Gadgets are not saved.

  @{b}Gadgets Only@{ub}
    Gadgets only will save only the lists: gadgets definitions, sort list,
    archive extract list, archive list list, archive add list, and double
    click list.  Prefs are not saved.

  @{b}Prefs and Gadgets in same file@{ub}
    Prefs and gadgets will save all of Rush's settings in the same
    file.

  @{b}Prefs and Gadgets in separate files@{ub} is the recommend method.

@{b}Prefs File@{ub}
  The string gadget labeled @{b}Prefs File@{ub} is the name of the main prefs
  file that Rush will save.

  To the right of the string gadget is a drawer gadget, this gadget
  will open an ASL file requester which can be used to select the main
  prefs file.  If ok is pressed in the ASL file requester the selected
  filename will be put in the @{i}prefs file@{ui} string gadget.

  The @{b}prefs file@{ub} string gadget will be disabled if the radio buttons are
  set to @{b}Gadgets Only@{ub}.

@{b}Gadgets File@{ub}
  The string gadget labeled @{b}Gadgets File@{ub} is name of the gadgets file
  that Rush will save.

  To the right of the string gadget is a drawer gadget, this gadget
  will open an ASL file requester which can be used to select the gadgets
  file.  If ok is pressed in the ASL file requester the selected
  filename will be put in the @{b}gadgets file@{ub} string gadget.

  The @{b}gadgets file@{ub} string gadget will be disabled if the radio buttons
  are set to @{b}Prefs without Gadgets@{ub} or @{b}Prefs and Gadgets in the same
  file@{ub}.

@{b}Create Icons@{ub}
  When the create icons checkbox is checked, icons will be saved for the
  prefs and gadgets files.  The default tool for the icons will be Rush,
  so the icons can be double clicked on and Rush will run with
  selected prefs file.

@endnode MENU_SAVESET

##
## MENU_LASTPATH
##
@node MENU_LASTPATH "Rush Help -- Lastpath Menu"
@{b}Lastpath Menu@{ub} @{i}Amiga-[1-0] @{ui}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The lastpaths menu displays the last ten directories that were loaded
into the @{"listviews" link LISTVIEW}.  If a directory is selected that directory will be
loaded into the listview on the active side.

@endnode MENU_LASTPATH

#####################################################################
## PREFS
##
@node PREFS "Rush Help -- Preference File"
@{b}Preference File@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The preference files for Rush are regular ASCII text files.  They can be
edited with a standard text editor.  Whenever a ';' is encountered the
rest of the line is ignored.

When Rush is loaded it looks for a preference file called rush.prefs
in a directory called Prefs of off the directory where Rush is
located, then in env:rush.

NOTE: It is not necessary that you understand the preference file, all
these options can be changed from within Rush using the preference
windows under the @{"Settings Menu" link MENU_SETTINGS}.

The following commands are available in preference files.

  Left <number>
  Top <number>
  Width <number>
  Height <number>
  DisplayID <modeid>
  Depth <number of bitplanes>
  Colors <rgb1 rgb2 rgb3 rgb4>
  SPens <detail block text shine shadow fill filltext background
         highlighttext menudetail menublock menutrim>
  LVPens <lvdir lvfile lvselect>
  LVFont FONT <fontname.font> SIZE <size>
  OscanType <text | graphics>
  ScreenFont FONT <fontname.font> SIZE <size>				  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}

  ProtectOptions <rwedasph>
  DeleteOptions <ask>
  CopyOptions <clonedate> <cloneprotect> <clonecomment> <askover>

  Pattern <pattern for pattern gadget>
  SortLeft SORT <ascend | dscend> BY <name | date | size>
           WITH <dirsfirst | dirsmixed>
  SortRight SORT <ascend | dscend> BY <name | date | size>
            WITH <dirsfirst | dirsmixed>
  GadgetSize WIDTH <width> HEIGHT <height> SPACE <distance between>

  Gadget NAME <display name> TYPE <@{"internal"link INTERNALCMDS} | @{"external"link EXTERNALCMDS} | device | noop>
         COMMAND <cmd>
  SortList DIR <dir> SORT <ascend | dscend> BY <name | date | size>
      WITH <dirsfirst | dirsmixed>

  ArchExtList EXT <pattern> PATTERN <template> COMMAND <cmd>
  ArchListList EXT <pattern> PATTERN <template> COMMAND <cmd>
  ArchAddList INPUT <file | stdin | cmdline> COMMAND <cmd>
  DClickList EXT <extension> PATTERN <template> COMMAND <cmd>

  Include <file>
  StartUpDirLeft <dir>
  StartUpDirRight <dir>
  RightButton COMMAND <cmd>
  MiddleButton COMMAND <cmd>
  Icons <prefs> <noprefs> <mkdir> <nomkdir> <autosel> <noautosel>
      <autorename> <noautorename>
  ScreenToFront <true/false>
  ConsoleString <con_string>
  ArchExtConStr <con_string>
  ArchListConStr <con_string>
  ArchAddConStr <con_string>
  DClickConStr <con_string>


Each of the commands are explained in more detail below.

@{b}Left <number>@{ub}
@{b}Top <number>@{ub}
@{b}Width <number>@{ub}
@{b}Height <number>@{ub}
  These are the coordinates of the window or screen that Rush will open
  on.  The defaults for left and top are 0, and for width and height it
  is the full size of the screen.  These can be set using the
  @{"Screen Mode settings window" link MENU_SCREENMODE}.

    example: Width 640

@{b}DisplayID <modeid>@{ub}
  This is the screen type that Rush will open on.  A displayid of
  0xffffffff means to open Rush as a window on the Workbench.
  The default screen type is the same as Workbench.  The displayid can
  be set using the @{"Screen Mode settings window" link MENU_SCREENMODE}.

    example: DisplayID 0x00019004

@{b}Depth <number of bitplanes>@{ub}
  This is used the specify the number of bitplanes for Rush's screen.
  The default is the same depth as Workbench.  The depth can be set
  using the @{"Screen Mode settings window" link MENU_SCREENMODE}.

      1 is   2 colors
      2 is   4 colors
      3 is   8 colors
      4 is  16 colors
      5 is  32 colors
      6 is  64 colors
      7 is 128 colors
      8 is 256 colors

    example: depth 3

@{b}Colors <rgb1 rgb2 rgb3 rgb4 ...>@{ub}
  This is used to specify the colors for Rush when it opens on a custom
  screen.  The first eight hex values for each group is the value for red,
  the second eight hex values is green, and the third eight hex values
  is blue.  The rgb values are hex values ranging from 0 to ffffffff,
  0 is the lowest intensity and ffffffff is the highest intensity.
  Using these 32-bit values allows the full AGA palette range to be
  selected.  Up to 8 colors can be specified, if there are more colors
  available, they will be made available to visitor programs.  There is
  a default set of colors build into Rush.  The screen colors can be
  set using the @{"Palette settings window" link MENU_PALETTE}.

    example: colors 11111111aaaaaaaa88888888 22222222bbbbbbbb00000000 ...

@{b}SPens <detail block text shine shadow fill filltext background
       highlighttext menudetail menublock menutrim>@{ub}
  This option is used to specify the pens used when Rush is on a custom
  screen.  The fist pen is the @{b}detail@{ub} pen that is used for detail
  information.  The second pen is the @{b}block@{ub} pen that is used for block or
  background information.  The third pen is the @{b}text@{ub} pen which is used for
  text.  The forth and fifth pens are the @{b}shine@{ub} and @{b}shadow@{ub} pens and they
  are used for the 3d newlook information.  The sixth pen is the @{b}fill@{ub} pen
  and is used for filling.  The seventh pens is the @{b}filltext@{ub} pen which is
  used for text in a fill area.  The eighth pen is the @{b}background@{ub} pen
  which is used for the background.  The ninth pen is the @{b}highlighttext@{ub}
  pen which is used for highlighted text.

  Under v39 of AmigaOS there are three additional pens which control the
  colors for the newlook titlebar and menus.  The three new pens are
  menu detail pen, menu block pen, and menu trim pen.

  The default is ~0, which uses the default pens for the system.  The
  screen pens can be set using the @{"Palette settings window" link MENU_PALETTE}.

    example: spens 0 1 1 2 1 3 1 0 2 1 2 1

@{b}LVPens <dir file select>@{ub}
  This option is used to specify which pens are used for the directory,
  file, and selected entries in the @{"listviews" link LISTVIEW}.  The first pen is the pen
  for directories, the second for files, and the third is for selected
  entries.  The default is 2 1 3.  The @{"listview" link LISTVIEW} pens can be set using
  the @{"Listview settings window" link MENU_LISTVIEW}.

    example: pens 2 1 3

@{b}LVFont FONT <name.font> SIZE <size>@{ub}
  This option is used to specify the font that is used for the @{"listviews" link LISTVIEW}.
  The font must be a non-proportional spaced font.  The default is
  topaz.font at 8 points.  The @{"listview" link LISTVIEW} font can be set using
  the @{"Listview  settings window" link MENU_LISTVIEW}.

    example: lvfont FONT topaz.font SIZE 8

@{b}OscanType <text | graphics>@{ub}
  This option is used to select the overscan type that Rush uses when
  it opens on a custom screen.  @{b}Text@{ub} is text overscan, and @{b}graphics@{ub} is
  graphics overscan.  @{b}Text@{ub} and @{b}graphics@{ub} overscan are set in the Workbench
  Overscan preference editor.  The overscan type can be set using the
  @{"Screen Mode settings window" link MENU_SCREENMODE}.

@{b}ScreenFont FONT <fontname.font> SIZE <size>@{ub}
  This option is used to specify the font that is used for the screen.	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
  The default is the Workbench screen font.  The screen font can be set	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
  using the @{"ScreenMode settings window" link MENU_SCREENMODE}.					  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}

    example: screenfont FONT topaz.font SIZE 8

@{b}ProtectOptions <rwedasph>@{ub}
  This option is used to specify the default protection bits for the
  protect command.  This option can be changed in Rush by holding down
  shift and pressing the protect @{"center gadget" link CENTERGADS} or using
  the @{"Internal Commands settings window" link MENU_INTCMDS}.

  The default is rwed.

    example: protectoptions rwed

@{b}DeleteOptions <ask>@{ub}
  This option is used to specify whether delete asks before it deletes
  files.  This option can be changed in Rush by holding down
  shift and press the delete @{"center gadget" link CENTERGADS} or using the
  @{"Internal Commands settings window" link MENU_INTCMDS}.

  If the ask option is on, a requester will open asking whether the
  file should be deleted.  See the @{"delete requester" link REQUESTERS 29} in the
  @{"requester" link REQUESTERS} section for more information on this requester.

  The default is to not ask.

    example: deleteoptions ask

@{b}CopyOptions <clonedate> <cloneprotect> <clonecomment> <askover> <unsetarch>@{ub}
  This option is used to specify options for copy.  When files are
  copied it allows the date, protect bits, and comments to be copied
  with files.  It also allows unsetting of the archive bit when
  copying files, and whether copy asks before overwriting a file.
  This option can be changed in Rush by holding down shift and press
  the copy @{"center gadget" link CENTERGADS} or using the
  @{"Internal Commands settings window" link MENU_INTCMDS}.

  If the askover write option is on, a requester will open asking
  whether the file should be overwritten.  See the @{"copy requester" link REQUESTERS 77}
  in the @{"requester" link REQUESTERS} section for more information on this requester.

  These options are used for both copy and move.  The default is copying
  the protection bits.

    example: copyoptions cloneprotect clonecomment ask

@{b}Pattern <AmigaDOS pattern>@{ub}
  This is the default wildcard pattern that use for @{"internal commands" link INTERNALCMDS}.
  It is what will appear in the @{"pattern gadget" link PATTERN}.  The default is "#?".
  
  See the @{"pattern gadget" link PATTERN} section for information on AmigaDOS wildcards.

    example: pattern ~(#?.info)

@{b}SortLeft SORT <ascend | dscend> BY <name | date | size>
         WITH <dirsfirst | dirsmixed>@{ub}
@{b}SortRight SORT <ascend | dscend> BY <name | date | size>
          WITH <dirsfirst | dirsmixed>@{ub}
  These options are used to select the default sort type for the
  @{"listviews" link LISTVIEW} on the left and right side.  The @{"listviews" link LISTVIEW} can be
  sorted by @{b}name@{ub}, @{b}date@{ub}, or @{b}size@{ub}, and @{b}ascending@{ub} or @{b}descending@{ub}.
  @{b}Ascending@{ub} is from smallest to biggest, and @{b}descending@{ub} is from
  biggest to smallest.  Directories can be mixed with files or be
  shown before files.

  Sorting can also be changed using @{"sort lists" link CONCEPTS 6 }, which can be
  configured using the @{"Listview settings window" link MENU_LISTVIEW}.

  The default is to sort ascending by name with directories and files
  mixed.

  Also see the @{b}sortlist@{ub} preference command below.

    example: sortleft SORT ascend BY name WITH dirsfirst

@{b}GadgetSize WIDTH <width> HEIGHT <height> SPACE <distance between>@{ub}
  This option is used to set the size of the @{"center gadgets" link CENTERGADS}.  The width
  and height of the gadgets and how much space is between each gadget
  can be specified.  These values are in pixels.  The @{b}width@{ub} must
  between 60 and 100 pixels, the @{b}height@{ub} must be greater then six pixels,
  and the @{b}space@{ub} between gadgets must be greater then or equal to zero.

  The defaults are a width of 80 pixels, height of 11 pixels, and
  spacing of 5 pixels for an interlace screen and 1 pixel for a
  non-interlace screen.

  The GadgetSize can be changed using the @{"Miscellaneous settings window" link MENU_MISC}.

    example: gadgetsize WIDTH 60 HEIGHT 12 SPACE 0

@{b}Gadget NAME <display name> TYPE <@{"internal"link INTERNALCMDS} | @{"external"link EXTERNALCMDS} | device | noop>
       COMMAND <cmd>@{ub}
  The gadget command is used to define @{"center gadgets" link CENTERGADS}.  They will be
  displayed in the order that they are specified in the preference file.
  The @{"center gadgets" link CENTERGADS} can be defined to execute @{"internal" link INTERNALCMDS} or @{"external" link EXTERNALCMDS}
  commands, load a directory on the active side, or do nothing at all.

  The @{"center gadgets" link CENTERGADS} can be configured using the
  @{"Edit Gadgets settings window" link MENU_EDITGADS}.

  See the @{"internal" link INTERNALCMDS} commands section for the list of internal commands.

    example: gadget NAME "All" TYPE internal COMMAND all

  See the @{"external" link EXTERNALCMDS} commands section for more information on external
  commands.

    example: gadget NAME "Calc" TYPE external COMMAND "calculator pubscreen %p"
  
  The gadget command can also load a directory on the active side when
  the gadget is pressed. 

    example: gadget NAME "MySrcCode" TYPE device COMMAND "work:source/CoolProgram"

  Gadgets can also be define to do nothing.

    example: gadget NAME "" TYPE noop COMMAND ""

@{b}SortList DIR <dir name> SORT <ascend | dscend> BY <name | date | size>
       WITH <dirsfirst | dirsmixed>@{ub}
  The sortlist command is used to specify sort options for specific
  directories.  This allows different directories to be automatically
  sorted differently when they are loaded.

  The directory name uses standard AmigaDOS pattern matching so
  wildcards can be used in it.

  See the @{"pattern gadget" link PATTERN} section for a description of AmigaDOS
  wildcard patterns.

  Also see @{"Concepts that are unique to Rush" link CONCEPTS} for a description of
  sort lists.

    example: sortlist DIR "work:dl#?" SORT dscend BY date WITH dirsfirst

@{b}ArchExtList EXT <extension> PATTERN <template> COMMAND <cmd>@{ub}
@{b}ArchListList EXT <extension> PATTERN <template> COMMAND <cmd>@{ub}
  These commands allow files to be automatically matched when the
  @{"archive extract" link INTERNALCMDS 154 } or @{"archive list" link INTERNALCMDS 173 } @{"internal commands" link INTERNALCMDS} are executed on a
  file.  The two commands have the same options, the difference is
  what list is searched.  @{b}ArchExtList@{ub} will be searched for the
  archive extract command, and @{b}ArchListList@{ub} will be searched for
  the archive list command.

  These commands will use an extension which will be compared with the
  filename of the archive and a template of the first few bytes of the
  file which will be compared with the file itself to find the correct
  archive command.  Both the extension and template do not need to be
  specified, if only one is specified, only that one will be used.

  For the extension, standard AmigaDOS pattern matching is used.  See
  the @{"pattern gadget" link PATTERN} section for more information on AmigaDOS pattern
  matching.

  For the template, up to the first 64 bytes of a file can be
  specified.  It can be specified in ASCII or as octal, base 8,
  numbers.  A question mark (?) can be used to match any character.
  An example of ASCII would be "Zoo ?.??  Archive".  An example of of
  octal would be "\120\113\003\004".  Octal numbers needs to be used
  if the characters are no printable.

  For the command, a %s will be substituted with the archive filename,
  a %p will be substituted with Rush's public screen name, and a %d
  will be substituted with the destination directory.

  The archive extract list and archive list list can be configured
  using the @{"Archive settings window" link MENU_ARCH}.

  Also see @{"archextract" link INTERNALCMDS 154 } and @{"archlist" link INTERNALCMDS 173 } in the @{"internal commands" link INTERNALCMDS} section.

  Also see @{"Concepts that are unique to Rush" link CONCEPTS} for a description of archive
  extract and archive list lists.

  examples:
    Only matching the extension:
        archextlist EXT "#?.zoo" TYPE "" COMMAND "zoo x %s"

    Only matching the file type:
        archextlist EXT "" TYPE "ZOO ?.?? Archive" COMMAND "zoo x %s"

    Both extension and type:
        archextlist EXT "#?.(lzh|lha)" TYPE "??-lh?-" COMMAND "lha x %s"

@{b}ArchAddList INPUT <file | stdin | cmdline> COMMAND <cmd> <QUOTE>@{ub}
  This command is used to create a list of archivers which can be used
  for creating archives with the @{"Archive Add" link INTERNALCMDS 188 } @{"internal command" link INTERNALCMDS}.  @{b}Input@{ub}
  sets the way the filelist will be given to the archive command.
  @{b}Command@{ub} is the archive command which can include %s and %f.  %s will
  be replaced by the archive name the user enters when creating the
  archive, and %f will be replaced by the filelist filename for the file
  option.  If the @{b}quote@{ub} option is given the filenames will be quoted
  with double quotes.

  The archive add list can be changed using the @{"Archive settings window" LINK MENU_ARCH}.

  Also see @{"ArchAdd" link INTERNALCMDS 188 } in the @{"internal commands" link INTERNALCMDS} section.

    example: archaddlist INPUT File COMMAND "lha -x -i%f a %s" QUOTE

@{b}DClickList EXT <extension> PATTERN <template> COMMAND <cmd>@{ub}
  This command is used to automatically match files when they are
  double click on in the @{"listviews" link LISTVIEW}.

  This command will use an extension which will be compared with the
  filename of the entry in the @{"listview" link LISTVIEW} and a template of the first few
  bytes of the file which will be compared with the file itself to find
  the correct double click command.  Both the extension and template do
  not need to be specified, if only one is specified, only that one
  will be used.

  For the extension, standard AmigaDOS pattern matching is used.  See
  the @{"pattern gadget" link PATTERN} section for more information on AmigaDOS pattern
  matching.

  For the type, up to the first 64 bytes of a file can be specified.
  It can be specified in ASCII or as octal, base 8, numbers.  A
  question mark (?) can be used to match any character.  An example of
  ASCII would be "Zoo ?.??  Archive".  An example of of octal would be
  "\120\113\003\004".  Octal numbers needs to be used if the characters
  are no printable.

  For the command, a %s will be substituted with the archive filename,
  a %p will be substituted with Rush's public screen name, and a %d
  will be substituted with the destination directory.

  Also see @{"Concepts that are unique to Rush" link CONCEPTS} for a description of double
  click lists.

  The double click list can be configured using the
  @{"DoubleClick settings window" LINK MENU_DCLICK}.

    example: dclicklist EXT "" PATTERN "FORM????ILBM" COMMAND "multiview %s pubscreen %p"

@{b}Include <file>@{ub}
  The include command is used to include another preference file.
  Multiple preference files could include the same gadget preference
  file so that only one gadget file need to be kept up to date.

    example: include "gadget.prefs"

@{b}StartUpDirLeft <dir>@{ub}
@{b}StartUpDirRight <dir>@{ub}
  These commands allow a directory to be automatically loaded in to one
  of the @{"listviews" link LISTVIEW} when Rush is started.  The no directory is specified
  the device list will be shown at startup.

  The startup directories can be configured using the
  @{"Miscellaneous settings window" link MENU_MISC}.

    example: startupdirleft "ram:"

@{b}RightButton COMMAND <cmd>@{ub}
@{b}MiddleButton COMMAND <cmd>@{ub}
  These commands allow the middle and right mouse buttons to be defined
  to execute @{"internal commands" link INTERNALCMDS}.

  The mouse buttons can be configured using the
  @{"Miscellaneous settings window" link MENU_MISC}.

    example:
        rightbutton COMMAND parent
        middlebutton COMMAND dirreread

@{b}Icons <prefs> <noprefs> <mkdir> <nomkdir> <autosel> <noautosel>
      <autorename> <noautorename>@{ub}
  This command select options related to icons.

  By default icons are created for both preference files and when
  directories are created.

  Whether icons are created for directories can be changed when
  directories are created using the @{"makedir window" link MAKEDIR_REQ}.

  Whether icons are created for preference files can be changed using
  the @{"Save Settings Window" link MENU_SAVESET}.

  Auto Icon Select can be changed using the @{"Auto Icon Select" link MENU_AUTOICONSEL} menuitem.

  Auto Icon Renaming can be changed when entries are renamed in the
  @{"rename window" link RENAME_REQ}.

    example: icons nomkdir   ;do not create icons for directories

@{b}ScreenToFront <true/false>@{ub}						  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
  This command causes Rush to be pulled to the front after any		  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
  @{"external command" link EXTERNALCMDS}.							  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
									  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
  The default is not to pulled the screen to the front.			  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
									  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
    example: ScreenToFront TRUE						  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}

@{b}ConsoleString <console_string>@{ub}						  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
@{b}ArchExtConStr <con_string>@{ub}						  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
@{b}ArchListConStr <con_string>@{ub}						  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
@{b}ArchAddConStr <con_string>@{ub}						  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
@{b}DClickConStr <con_string>@{ub}						  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
  The console string is the string that specifics the console window for  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
  @{"external command" link EXTERNALCMDS}, archive extract, archive list, archive add, and	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
  double click commands.						  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
									  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
  The console window can be changed in the @{"External Commands settings window " link MENU_EXTCMDS}.	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
									  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
    example: consolestring "con:%c/200/640/999/%t/screen %p"		  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}

@endnode PREFS

##
## INTERNALCMDS
##
@node INTERNALCMDS "Rush Help -- Internal Commands"
@{b}Internal Commands@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

Internal commands are the commands that are build into Rush that can be
specified in the @{"gadget" link PREFS 257 } command in the @{"preference files" link PREFS}.

The internal commands are also listed in the @{"Edit Gadgets" link MENU_EDITGADS} window
and the @{"Miscellaneous" link MENU_MISC} window.

The internal commands that are available are:  noop, all, clear,
invert, compareselected, copy, rename, move, delete, protect, makedir,
size, archextract, archlist, parent, root, devicelist, dirreread,
about, iconify, quit, copydirtoclip, copyseltoclip, pastedirfromclip,
showerrors, screenmode, palette, editgadgets, listviewoptions,
archiveoptions, internalcommands, miscellaneous, loadsettings, and
savesettings.

@{b}Noop@{ub}
  The noop command does nothing.

@{b}All@{ub}
  All will select all the files in the @{"listview" link LISTVIEW} that match the pattern
  in the @{"pattern gadget" link PATTERN}.

@{b}Clear@{ub}
  Clear will unselect all the files in the @{"listview" link LISTVIEW} that match the
  pattern in the @{"pattern gadget" link PATTERN}.

  If shift is held down when the Clear gadget is pressed it will
  unselect all selected files, including files on the source and
  destination side and in the @{"select list" link CONCEPTS 68 }.  When shift is used
  with clear, the @{"pattern gadget" link PATTERN} is not used.

@{b}Invert@{ub}
  Invert will unselect the selected files and select the unselected files
  in the @{"listview" link LISTVIEW}.

@{b}CompareSelected@{ub}
  CompareSelected will compare the selected names on the active side
  with names on the destination side, if the name exist on the
  destination side it is unselected from the source side.  If the name
  does not exist on the destination side it stays selected on the source
  side.  This command does not compare the contents of the files, it
  just checks to see if the file exists.

@{b}Copy@{ub}
  Copy will copy files from the source side to the destination side.  If
  one of the selected entry is a directory, all files in the directory
  that match the @{"pattern gadget" link PATTERN} will be recursively copied.

  If an entry on the source side is a file link it will be copied to the
  destination as a file.  If an entry on the source side is a directory
  link it will be copied to the destination as a directory and all the
  files in the directory link will be copied also.

  Pressing the Copy gadget while shift is held down will open the
  @{"copy/move options window" link COPYMOVE_OPTIONS} which allows the copy and move options to be
  set.  The options that can be set are:  clone date, clone protection
  bits, clone comment, and ask overwrite.  These options can also be
  changed using the @{"Internal Commands settings window" link MENU_INTCMDS}.

  See the @{"requesters" link REQUESTERS} section for a description of the requesters
  that can come up when copying files.

@{b}Rename@{ub}
  Rename will rename a file or directory.  The @{"Rename window" link RENAME_REQ} will open
  allowing a new name to be entered.

  Files can be renamed to a different directory as long as it is still on
  the same device.

  See the @{"requesters" link REQUESTERS} section for a description of the requesters
  that can come up when renaming files.

@{b}Move@{ub}
  Move will move files from the source side to the destination side.  If
  one of the selected entry is a directory, all files in the directory
  that match the @{"pattern gadget" link PATTERN} will be recursively moved.

  If the source and destination are on the same device, the source will
  just be renamed to the destination.  If the files are not on the same
  device, files will be copied and then deleted from the source.

  If an entry on the source side is a file link it will be moved to the
  destination as a file.  If an entry on the source side is a directory
  link it will be moved to the destination as a directory and all the
  files in the directory link will be moved too.  Since moving on the
  same device just renames the file or directory, the file or directory
  will remain a link.

  Pressing the Move gadget while shift is held down will open the
  @{"copy/move options window" link COPYMOVE_OPTIONS} which allows the copy and move options to be
  set.  The options that can be set are:  clone date, clone protection
  bits, clone comment, and ask overwrite.  These options can also be
  changed using the @{"Internal Commands settings window" link MENU_INTCMDS}.

  See the @{"requesters" link REQUESTERS} section for a description of the requesters
  that can come up when moving files.

@{b}Delete@{ub}
  Delete will delete files or directories from the source side.  If one
  of the selected entry is a directory, all the files in the directory
  that match the @{"pattern gadget" link PATTERN} will be recursively deleted.

  File links will be deleted like normal files.  Directory links will be
  deleted as if they are files.  This means files inside a directory
  link will NOT be deleted.

  Pressing the Delete gadget while shift is held down will open the
  @{"delete options window" link DELETE_OPTIONS} which allows the delete options to be set.  The
  only option that can be set for delete is:  ask delete.

  See the @{"requesters" link REQUESTERS} section for a description of the requesters
  that can come up when deleting files.

@{b}Protect@{ub}
  Protect will change the protection bits of a file or directory.  If one
  of the selected entries is a directory, all the files in the directory
  that match the @{"pattern gadget" link PATTERN} will recursively have there protection
  bits changed.

  File links will have there protection bits changed like normal files.
  Directory links will NOT be recursively protected.  This is because
  @{b}protect@{ub}, @{b}size@{ub}, and @{b}delete@{ub} all use the same recursive directory scanning
  function.

  Pressing the Protect gadget while shift is held down will open the
  @{"protect options window" link PROTECT_OPTIONS} which allows the protection bits to be set.

  See the @{"requesters" link REQUESTERS} section for a description of the requesters
  that can come up when protecting files.

@{b}Makedir@{ub}
  Makedir will create a directory.  When this command is executed the
  @{"makedir window" link MAKEDIR_REQ} will be opened.  By default the directory name of the
  source side will be displayed in the string gadget.  The directory can
  be made anywhere in the system not just in the directory on the active
  side.

  See the @{"requesters" link REQUESTERS} section for a description of the requesters
  that can come up when making directories.

@{b}Size@{ub}
  Size totals up the number of bytes in a directory.  It recursively goes
  through directories and adds up the file sizes of files that match the
  @{"pattern gadget" link PATTERN}.

  Size will NOT enter directory links and will NOT add file links to
  the total size.

  See the @{"requesters" link REQUESTERS} section for a description of the requesters
  that can come up when sizing directories.

@{b}ArchExtract@{ub}
  Archive extract will @{i}extract@{ui} files from any archive type.  It searches
  through the @{"archive extract list" link CONCEPTS 30 } to find the correct archive extracting
  program to use on the file.  Only files are checked, directories are
  skipped.

  Archives will be extracted to the destination directory.  Currently a
  destination directory must be selected for archive extract to work.

  The archive extracting program will be executed with the AmigaDOS
  System() function.  This means the default UserShell will be used for
  the console and the window will close after the program has extracted
  the archive.  If the archive program returns an error, the window will
  remain open until the close gadget is selected so the error message
  can be seen.

  The @{"archive extract list" link CONCEPTS 30 } can be changed using the
  @{"Archive settings window" link MENU_ARCH}.

  The console window used for archive extract can be changed in the
  @{"External Commands settings window " link MENU_EXTCMDS}.

@{b}ArchList@{ub}
  Archive list will @{i}list@{ui} files in any archive type.  It searches
  through the @{"archive list list" link CONCEPTS 30 } to find the correct archive listing
  program to use on the file.  Only files are checked, directories are
  skipped.

  The archive listing program will be executed with the AmigaDOS
  System() function.  This means the default UserShell will be used for
  the console and the window will close after the program has extracted
  the archive.  If the archive program returns an error, the window will
  remain open until the close gadget is selected so the error message
  can be seen.

  The @{"archive list list" link CONCEPTS 30 } can be changed using the
  @{"Archive settings window" link MENU_ARCH}.

  The console window used for archive list can be changed in the
  @{"External Commands settings window " link MENU_EXTCMDS}.

@{b}ArchAdd@{ub}
  ArchiveAdd is used to create an archive file.  The @{"archive add window" link ARCHADD_REQ}
  will be used to prompt the user for the archive type and filename. 

  The archive program will be executed with the AmigaDOS System()
  function.  This means the default UserShell will be used for the
  console and the window will close after the program has added files to
  the archive.  If the archive program returns an error, the window will
  remain open until the close gadget is selected so the error messages
  can be seen.

  The archive add programs can be changed using the
  @{"Archive settings window" link MENU_ARCH}.

  The console window used for archive add can be changed in the
  @{"External Commands settings window " link MENU_EXTCMDS}.

@{b}Parent@{ub}
  Parent loads the parent directory of the active side.  If the root
  of the device is already being shown the device list will be
  displayed.

@{b}Root@{ub}
  Root loads the root directory of the active side.  If the
  root directory is already being shown it will be read again.

@{b}DeviceList@{ub}
  DeviceList will show the device list on the active side.  If
  the device list is already being shown it will be updated.

@{b}DirReRead@{ub}
  DirReRead rereads the directory on the active side.  If the device
  list is being shown it will be updated.

@{b}Info@{ub}
  Info opens the @{"info window" link INFO_REQ} for the selected files on the active side.

@{b}FileFind@{ub}
  search the selected directrories for a specified filename or		  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
  pattern.								  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}

The following internal commands are already available in the menus,
but they can be used in the center gadgets also.

@{b}About@{ub}
  About shows the about requester.  This is the same as pressing Amiga-?
  or selecting @{"About..." link MENU_ABOUT} from the @{"Project menu" link MENU_PROJECT}.

@{b}Iconify@{ub}
  Iconify iconifies Rush down to an AppIcon on Workbench.  This the
  same as pressing Amiga-I or selecting @{"Iconify" link MENU_ICONIFY} from the
  @{"Project menu" link MENU_PROJECT}.

@{b}Quit@{ub}
  Quit quits Rush.  This the same a pressing Amiga-Q or selecting @{"Quit" link MENU_QUIT}
  from the @{"Project menu" link MENU_PROJECT}.

@{b}CopyDirToClip@{ub}
  Copy Directory will copy the directory name on the active side to the
  clipboard.  This is the same a pressing Amiga-X or selecting
  @{"Copy Directory" link MENU_COPYDIR} from the @{"Edit menu" link MENU_EDIT}.
  
@{b}CopySelToClip@{ub}
  Copy Selected will copy the selected entries on the active side to the
  clipboard.  The directory name is prepended to each entry and each entry
  is separated by a space and quoted with double quotes.  This is the
  same a pressing Amiga-C or selecting @{"Copy Selected" link MENU_COPYSEL} from the @{"Edit menu" link MENU_EDIT}.
  
@{b}PasteDirFromClip@{ub}
  Paste Directory pastes from the clipboard to the active side's
  directory, and the directory is loaded.  This is the same a pressing
  Amiga-V or selecting @{"Paste Directory" link MENU_PASTE} from the @{"Edit menu" link MENU_EDIT}.
  
@{b}ShowErrors@{ub}
  ShowErrors opens the @{"showerrors window" link MENU_SHOWERRORS} showing all the AmigaDOS errors that
  Rush has encountered.  This is the same as pressing Amiga-E or
  selecting @{"ShowErrors" link MENU_SHOWERRORS} from the @{"Commands menu" link MENU_COMMANDS}.

@{b}ScreenMode@{ub}
  ScreenMode will open the @{"ScreenMode settings window" link MENU_SCREENMODE}.  This is the same
  as pressing Amiga-S or selecting @{"Screen Mode..." link MENU_SCREENMODE} from the
  @{"Settings menu" link MENU_SETTINGS}.
  
@{b}Palette@{ub}
  Palette will open the @{"Palette settings window" link MENU_PALETTE}.  This is the same as
  pressing Amiga-P or selecting @{"Palette..." link MENU_PALETTE} from the @{"Settings menu" link MENU_SETTINGS}.
  
@{b}EditGadgets@{ub}
  EditGadgets will open the @{"EditGadgets settings window" link MENU_EDITGADS}.  This is the
  same as pressing Amiga-G or selecting @{"Edit Gadgets..." link MENU_EDITGADS} from the
  @{"Settings menu" link MENU_SETTINGS}.
  
@{b}ListviewOptions@{ub}
  ListviewOptions will open the @{"Listview settings window" link MENU_LISTVIEW}.  This is the
  same as pressing Amiga-L or selecting @{"Listview..." link MENU_LISTVIEW} from the
  @{"Settings menu" link MENU_SETTINGS}.

@{b}ArchiveOptions@{ub}
  ArchiveOptions will open the @{"Archive settings window" link MENU_ARCH}.  This is the
  same as pressing Amiga-A or selecting @{"Archive..." link MENU_ARCH} from the
  @{"Settings menu" link MENU_SETTINGS}.
  
@{b}InternalCommands@{ub}
  InternalCommands will open the @{"Internal Commands settings window" link MENU_INTCMDS}.
  This is the same as pressing Amiga-N or selecting @{"Internal Commands..." link MENU_INTCMDS}
  from the @{"Settings menu" link MENU_SETTINGS}.

@{b}Miscellaneous@{ub}
  Miscellaneous will open the @{"Miscellaneous settings window" link MENU_MISC}.  This is
  the same as pressing Amiga-M or selecting @{"Miscellaneous..." link MENU_MISC} from
  the @{"Settings menu" link MENU_SETTINGS}.

@{b}LoadSettings@{ub}
  LoadSettings will open the ASL file requester.  This is the
  same as pressing Amiga-E or selecting @{"Load Settings..." link MENU_LOADSET} from the
  @{"Settings menu" link MENU_SETTINGS}.

@{b}AppendSettings@{ub}
  AppendSettings will open the ASL file requester.  This is the
  same as pressing Amiga-R or selecting @{"Append Settings..." link MENU_APPENDSET} from the
  @{"Settings menu" link MENU_SETTINGS}.

@{b}SaveSettings@{ub}
  SaveSettings will open the @{"Save Settings window" link MENU_SAVESET}.  This is the
  same as pressing Amiga-W or selecting @{"Save Settings..." link MENU_SAVESET} from the
  @{"Settings menu" link MENU_SETTINGS}.

@endnode INTERNALCMDS

##
## EXTERNALCMDS
##
@node EXTERNALCMDS "Rush Help -- External Commands"
@{b}External Commands@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

External commands are standard AmigaDOS commands that can be executed
from within Rush.  External commands are executed with the AmigaDOS
System() function so the default UserShell will be used for the console
and the window will close after the program has executed.  If the
external command returns an error, the window will remain open until
the close gadget is selected so the error message can be seen.
External commands are configured using the @{"EditGadgets settings window" link MENU_EDITGADS}.

There are three escape sequences that can be specified in the command:

  %s will be replaced with the selected file or directory name.

  %p will be replaced with the public screen name for Rush.

  %d will be replaced with the destination directory name.


External commands are executed from the directory where Rush is
located, this allows commands to be found relative to Rush's
program directory.

For example "scripts/format_disk" could be used to execute the script
"format_disk" in a directory called "scripts" off of the directory
where Rush is located.

@endnode EXTERNALCMDS

##
## COPYMOVE_OPTIONS
##
@node COPYMOVE_OPTIONS "Rush Help -- Copy/Move"
@{b}Copy and Move Options Window@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The copy/move options window is used to set the options for the @{"copy" link INTERNALCMDS 46 }
and @{"move" link INTERNALCMDS 75 } @{"internal commands" link INTERNALCMDS}.

  Clone Protection  - Set the protection bits on the destination file
                      the same as the source file.  If this option is
                      off the destination file will have protection
                      bits set to RWED.

  Clone Date        - Set the date of the destination file the same as
                      the source file.  If this option is off the
                      destination file's date will be set to the
                      current time.

  Clone Comment     - Set the comment of the destination file the same
                      as the source file.  If this option is off the
                      destination file will have no comment.

  Ask Overwrite     - Ask the user about overwriting files if the file
                      already exists.

  Unset Archive Bit - Remove the archive bit of the destination file
                      when it is copied.

The Copy and Move options can also be changed in the
@{"Internal Commands settings window" link MENU_INTCMDS}.

@endnode COPYMOVE_OPTIONS

##
## DELETE_OPTIONS
##
@node DELETE_OPTIONS "Rush Help -- Delete"
@{b}Delete Options Window@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The delete options window is used to set the options for the
@{"delete" link INTERNALCMDS 100 } @{"internal command" link INTERNALCMDS}.

  Confirm Delete - Ask the user before deleting files.

The Delete options can also be changed in the
@{"Internal Commands settings window" link MENU_INTCMDS}.

@endnode DELETE_OPTIONS

##
## PROTECT_OPTIONS
##
@node PROTECT_OPTIONS "Rush Help -- Protect"
@{b}Protect Options Window@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The protect options window is used to set the options for the
@{"protect" link INTERNALCMDS 116 } @{"internal command" link INTERNALCMDS}.

  H bit      - The H bit is currently not used by AmigaDOS.

  Script     - Set the script bit.

  Pure       - Set the pure bit.

  Archived   - Set the archived bit.

  Readable   - Set the readable bit.

  Writable   - Set the writable bit.

  Executable - Set the executable bit.

  Deletable  - Set the deletable bit.

The Protect options can also be changed in the
@{"Internal Commands settings window" link MENU_INTCMDS}.

@endnode PROTECT_OPTIONS

##
## INFO_REQ
##
@node INFO_REQ "Rush Help -- Info"
@{b}Info Window@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The Info window shows information on a file or directory.  The Info
window is shown when the @{"info" link INTERNALCMDS 219 } @{"internal command" link INTERNALCMDS} is used.

@{b}Name@{ub}
  This is the filename of the file or directory which is being shown.

@{b}Type@{ub}
  This is the type of file that is being shown, it will show one of
  the following:

      file - standard file

      directory - standard directory

      file hardlink to xxx - hardlink to file xxx

      directory hardlink to xxx - hardlink to directory xxx

@{b}Date@{ub}
  This is the date of the file or directory.

@{b}Comment@{ub}
  This string gadget is the comment or filenote of the file.

@{b}Protection bits@{ub}
  The protection bits show the current protection bits for the file
  or directory.

@{b}Save@{ub}
  Save will save the comment and protection bits to the file and
  then show the next selected file.

@{b}Next@{ub}
  Next will show info on the next selected file.

@{b}Cancel@{ub}
  Cancel will stop info.

@endnode INFO_REQ

##
## MAKEDIR_REQ
##
@node MAKEDIR_REQ "Rush Help -- Makedir"
@{b}Makedir Window@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The Makedir window is used to make a directory.

The makedir window contains a string gadget where the name of the
directory to be created is entered.  The name should include the the
full pathname of the directory to be created.  Pressing return while
in the string gadget is the same as pressing OK.  Pressing		  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
@{i}shift-return@{ui} while in the string gadget is the same as		  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
pressing Apply.								  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}

@{b}Create Icons@{ub}
  If the create icons checkbox is check an icon will be created for the
  directory.  The drawer icon will be the default system drawer icon.

@{b}OK@{ub}
  OK will make the directory in the string gadget.

@{b}Apply@{ub}								  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
  Apply will make the directory in the string gadget and keep the	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
  window opened so more directories can be created.			  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}

@{b}Cancel@{ub}
  Cancel will not make the directory.

Create Icons option can also be changed in the
@{"Internal Commands settings window" link MENU_INTCMDS}.

@endnode MAKEDIR_REQ

##
## MULTIASSIGN_REQ
##
@node MULTIASSIGN_REQ "Rush Help -- MultiAssign"
@{b}Multiple Assign Window@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The Multiple Assign window is used to select different directories
from a multiple assign.

The Multiple Assign window will only be able to be open if the
@{"multiple assign gadget" link MULTIASSIGN} is enabled and the current directory being show
in the @{"listview" link LISTVIEW} is a multiple assign.

The window shows a listview of all the directories in the multiple
assign.  Selecting a directory from the listview and pressing OK, or
double clicking on an entry will load that directory into the
@{"listview" link LISTVIEW}.

@endnode MULTIASSIGN_REQ

##
## RENAME_REQ
##
@node RENAME_REQ "Rush Help -- Rename"
@{b}Rename Window@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The Rename window is used to rename a file or directory.

The Rename window is opened by the @{"rename" link INTERNALCMDS 65 } @{"internal command" link INTERNALCMDS}.

The string gadget will contain the current name for the file or
directory.  Pressing return while the cursor is in the string gadget
is the same as pressing OK.

@{b}Auto Icon Rename@{ub}
  If the Auto Icon Rename checkbox is check and an icon exists for the
  entry being renamed, the icon will also be rename.  If an icon is
  renamed its parent file or directory will also be renamed.

@{b}OK@{ub}
  OK will rename the file and go on to the next selected file.

@{b}Cancel@{ub}
  Cancel will not rename the file and will abort the rename command.

Auto Icon Rename can also be changed in the
@{"Internal Commands settings window" link MENU_INTCMDS}.

@endnode RENAME_REQ

##
## ARCHADD_REQ
##
@node ARCHADD_REQ "Rush Help -- Archive Add"
@{b}Archive Add Window@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The Archive Add window is used to create an archive.

The string gadget labeled @{b}Archive@{ub} is where the archive name is
entered.  The full path and filename are entered.

The listview on the left is used to select the archive type.

Archive types can be configured using the @{"Archive settings window" LINK MENU_ARCH}.

@endnode ARCHADD_REQ

##
## MIN_PALETTE
##
@node MIN_PALETTE "Rush Help -- Palette"
@{b}Palette Window@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The Palette window is used to select the colors for the center
gadgets, the colors of the text in the @{"listviews" link LISTVIEW} and the 
screen pens.

The Palette window opens a small window showing 2, 4, or 8 colors.
Selecting one of the colors will close the window and select that
color.  The closegadget of the window can be used to abort
selecting a color.

@endnode MIN_PALETTE

##
## COMMENT_REQ
##
@node COMMENT_REQ "Rush Help -- Comment"
@{b}Comment Window@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The Comment window is used to change the comment on a file or
directory.

The string gadget will contain the current comment for the file or
directory.  Pressing return while the cursor is in the string gadget
is the same as pressing OK.

@{b}OK@{ub}
  OK will change the comment for the file or directory and go on to
  the next selected file or directory.

@{b}All@{ub}
  All will change the comment for all the selected entries to the
  comment that is currently in the string gadget.  @{i}Esc@{ui} can
  be used to abort the Comment operation if All is used.

@{b}Cancel@{ub}
  Cancel will not change the comment on the current entry, and will
  abort the Comment operation.

@endnode COMMENT_REQ

##
## AREXX_STRING_REQ
##
@node AREXX_STRING_REQ "Rush Help -- Arexx String Window"
@{b}Arexx String Window@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

The Arexx string requester is used to prompt for a string from Arexx.	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
Pressing return while the string gadget is active is the same a		  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
pressing OK.								  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}

@{b}OK@{ub}
  The contents of the string gadget are returned to Arexx in the
  RESULT variable, and RC is set to zero.

@{b}Cancel@{ub}
  The Arexx RC variable is set to one.

See the @{"string requester" link AREXX} Arexx command.

@endnode AREXX_STRING_REQ

##
## FILE_FIND_REQ
##
@node FILE_FIND_REQ "Rush Help -- File Find Window"
@{b}File Find Window@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

File find is made up of two windows, the first window prompts for a	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
filename to search for, the second window displays a list of found	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
files.									  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}

@{b}Filename prompt window@{ub}
  The first window has only a string gadget that is used to enter the	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
  filename to find.  The filename can include AmigaDOS wildcards.	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}

  @{b}OK@{ub}
    All the selected directories on the active side are scanned,
    searching for the filename in the string gadget.

  @{b}Cancel@{ub}
    Close the file find window without searching.

@{b}File list window@{ub}
  The second window has a listview which shows all the files which	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
  match the filename.  If one of these files is selected and OK is	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
  pressed, the directory the file is located in will be loaded on the	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
  active side.								  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}

  While directories are being scanned Escape can be used to abort	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
  the scan.								  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}

  @{b}OK@{ub}
    Load the directory of the selected file on the active side.

  @{b}Cancel@{ub}
    Close the file find window without loading any directories.

See the @{"pattern gadget" link PATTERN} section for information on AmigaDOS wildcards.

@endnode AREXX_FIND_REQ

##
## Arexx
##
@node AREXX "Rush Help -- Arexx"
@{b}Arexx@{ub}
@{b}ŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

Rush's Arexx port name is shown in the About requester and it is the
same as the public screen name if Rush is opened on a custom screen.

This section is new to release 1.1, release 1.1 is the first release	  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}
of Rush which has an Arexx interface.					  @{fg shine}@{B}|@{UB}@{fg text}

The following is a list of Arexx functions Rush supports, each one is
described below.

  Requester         IsIconify         SetScreenFont      GetDeleteOptions
  StringRequester   SetScreenMode     GetScreenFont      SetProtectOptions
  StatusMsg         GetScreenMode     SetListviewFont    GetProtectOptions
  SetActiveSide     SetPalette        GetListviewFont    SetSort
  GetActiveSide     GetPalette        SetPattern         GetSort
  SetDirectory      SetScreenPens     GetPattern         GetSelected
  GetDirectory      GetScreenPens     SetCopyOptions     GetPubScreenName
  RushToFront       SetListviewPens   GetCopyOptions
  RushToBack        GetListviewPens   SetDeleteOptions

The follow @{"internal commands" link INTERNALCMDS} are also Arexx functions from within Rush,
they perform the same operation as they do when they are used in
@{"center gadgets" link CENTERGADS}.

  @{"Noop" link INTERNALCMDS 18 }             @{"Makedir" link INTERNALCMDS 133 }      @{"About" link INTERNALCMDS 226 }             @{"ListviewOptions" link INTERNALCMDS 274 }
  @{"All" link INTERNALCMDS 21 }              @{"Size" link INTERNALCMDS 143 }         @{"Iconify" link INTERNALCMDS 230 }           @{"ArchiveOptions" link INTERNALCMDS 279 }
  @{"Clear" link INTERNALCMDS 25 }            @{"ArchExtract" link INTERNALCMDS 154 }  @{"Quit" link INTERNALCMDS 235 }              @{"InternalCommands" link INTERNALCMDS 284 }
  @{"Invert" link INTERNALCMDS 34 }           @{"ArchList" link INTERNALCMDS 173 }     @{"CopyDirToClip" link INTERNALCMDS 239 }     @{"Miscellaneous" link INTERNALCMDS 289 }
  @{"CmpSelected" link INTERNALCMDS 38 }      @{"ArchAdd" link INTERNALCMDS 188 }      @{"CopySelToClip" link INTERNALCMDS 244 }     @{"LoadSettings" link INTERNALCMDS 294 }
  @{"Copy" link INTERNALCMDS 46 }             @{"Parent" link INTERNALCMDS 202 }       @{"PasteDirFromClip" link INTERNALCMDS 250 }  @{"AppendSettings" link INTERNALCMDS 299 }
  @{"Rename" link INTERNALCMDS 65 }           @{"Root" link INTERNALCMDS 207 }         @{"ShowErrors" link INTERNALCMDS 255 }        @{"SaveSettings" link INTERNALCMDS 304 }
  @{"Move" link INTERNALCMDS 75 }             @{"DeviceList" link INTERNALCMDS 211 }   @{"ScreenMode" link INTERNALCMDS 260 }
  @{"Delete" link INTERNALCMDS 100}           @{"DirReRead" link INTERNALCMDS 215 }    @{"Palette" link INTERNALCMDS 265 }
  @{"Protect" link INTERNALCMDS 116}          @{"Info" link INTERNALCMDS 219 }         @{"EditGadgets" link INTERNALCMDS 269 }


@{b}Requester GADGETS/A,BODY/A@{ub}

  Posts an Intuition requester with @{i}body @{ui}as the text and @{i}gadgets @{ui}as
  the buttons.

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}gadgets @{ui}- List of gadgets that should be used in the requester, multiple
              buttons are separated my vertical bars(|).
    @{i}body @{ui}   - The main text for the requester.  Newline characters
              can be entered as ascii newline character 10 or as the
              two characters "\n".  In Arexx is is easier to use "\n".

  RESULTS
    @{i}result @{ui}- Number of the button that is pressed.  The buttons are
             numbered from left to right starting with one and the
             last button is all was zero.

@{b}StringRequester PROMPT/A,DEFAULT@{ub}

  Prompts the user for a string, @{i}prompt@{ui} will be displayed in the
  in the requester window above the string gadget, @{i}default@{ui} if given
  will used for the default text in the string gadget.

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}prompt @{ui} - prompt text to display above the string gadget,
              only one line of text can be specified
    @{i}default @{ui}- optional default text for the string gadget

  RESULTS
    @{i}result @{ui}- if OK is selected this will contain the contents
             of the string gadget, if Cancel is selectec this will
             contain the string RESULT
    @{i}rc @{ui}    - 0 if OK is selected, 1 of Cancel is selected

  SEE ALSO
    @{"Arexx String Requester" link AREXX_STRING_REQ}

@{b}StatusMsg MSG/A@{ub}

  Displays @{i}msg@{ui} in the @{"status text gadget" link STATUS}.

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}msg @{ui}- Text to display in the status area.

  RESULTS
    @{i}none @{ui}

  SEE ALSO
    @{"Status Text Gadget" link STATUS}

@{b}SetActiveSide SIDE/A@{ub}

  Changes the active side.  @{i}Side@{ui} can be LEFT, RIGHT, or OTHER.

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}side @{ui}- left, right, or other

  RESULTS
    @{i}none @{ui}

@{b}GetActiveSide@{ub}

  Gets the active side.  Returns LEFT if the left side is active,
  RIGHT if the right side is active.

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}none @{ui}

  RESULTS
    @{i}result @{ui}- which side is active: left or right

@{b}SetDirectory DIR/A,SIDE@{ub}

  Sets the directory to @{i}dir@{ui} and reads the directory.  By
  default it effects the active side, side can be used to specify a
  different side.

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}dir @{ui} - directory to load
    @{i}side @{ui}- which side to load the directory: active, left,
                    right, or other

  RESULTS
    @{i}none @{ui}

  SEE ALSO
    @{"Directory String Gadget" link DIRSTRGAD}

@{b}GetDirectory SIDE@{ub}

  Gets the directory name that is loaded on @{i}side@{ui}.  By default
  this gets the directory on the active side.

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}side @{ui}- which side to get the directory name from:active,
                    left, right, or other

  RESULTS
    @{i}result @{ui}- directory name, NULL if device list
    @{i}RC @{ui}    - 0 if directory, 1 if device list

  SEE ALSO
    @{"Directory String Gadget" link DIRSTRGAD}

@{b}RushToFront@{ub}

  Pulls the screen that Rush is on to the front, if Rush is a window
  it also pulls the window to the front of all other windows.

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}none @{ui}

  RESULTS
    @{i}none @{ui}

@{b}RushToBack@{ub}

  Pushes the screen that Rush is on to the back, if Rush is a window
  it also pushes the window to the back of all other windows.

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}none @{ui}

  RESULTS
    @{i}none @{ui}

@{b}IsIconify@{ub}

  Test if Rush is iconified.

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}none @{ui}

  RESULTS
    @{i}result @{ui}- 0 if NOT iconified, 1 if iconified

  SEE ALSO
    @{"Iconify menuitem" link MENU_ICONIFY}, @{"Iconify Internal command" link INTERNALCMDS 230}

@{b}SetScreenMode ID/K,WB/S,DEPTH/N,LEFT/K,TOP/K,WIDTH/K,HEIGHT/K,OVERSCAN/K@{ub}

  Change Rush's screen attributes.  Not all the arguments need to be
  specified, values that are not specified will not be changed.

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}id @{ui}      - display id of the screen to open, if started with 0x
               it is considered hex, otherwise decimal
    @{i}wb @{ui}      - if this switch is specified Rush will open as
               a window on the Workbench, this has persidence over @{i}id @{ui}
    @{i}depth @{ui}   - depth of the screen to open if on a custom screen
    @{i}left @{ui}    - left edge of the screen or window
    @{i}top @{ui}     - top edge of the screen or window
    @{i}width @{ui}   - width of the screen or window
    @{i}height @{ui}  - height of the screen or window
    @{i}overscan @{ui}- overscan type, TEXT or GRAPHICS

  RESULTS
    @{i}none @{ui}

  SEE ALSO
    @{"ScreenMode settings window" link MENU_SCREENMODE}, Preference commands: @{"displayid" link PREFS 80}, @{"depth" link PREFS 88},
    @{"left" link PREFS 69}, @{"top" link PREFS 69}, @{"width" link PREFS 69}, @{"height" link PREFS 69}, @{"overscan" link PREFS 157}

@{b}GetScreenMode@{ub}

  Gets the current screenmode information.  Returns a string that
  contains the display id, depth, leftedge, topedge, width, height, and
  overscan type, in that order.

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}none @{ui}

  RESULTS
    @{i}result @{ui}- screenmode info

  SEE ALSO
    @{"ScreenMode settings window" link MENU_SCREENMODE}, Preference commands: @{"displayid" link PREFS 80}, @{"depth" link PREFS 88},
    @{"left" link PREFS 69}, @{"top" link PREFS 69}, @{"width" link PREFS 69}, @{"height" link PREFS 69}, @{"overscan" link PREFS 157}

@{b}SetPalette PEN/N/A,RED/K/A,GREEN/K/A,BLUE/K/A@{ub}

  Set @{i}pen@{ui} to the color specified by @{i}red,@{ui} @{i}green,@{ui} and @{i}blue.@{ui}

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}pen @{ui}  - pen number to set
    @{i}red @{ui}  - red value, if it begins with 0x it is considered hex,
            otherwise decimal
    @{i}green @{ui}- green value, if it begins with 0x it is considered hex,
            otherwise decimal
    @{i}blue @{ui} - blue value, if it begins with 0x it is considered hex,
            otherwise decimal

  RESULTS
    @{i}none @{ui}

  SEE ALSO
    @{"Palette settings window" link MENU_PALETTE }, Preference command: @{"colors" link PREFS 104}

@{b}GetPalette PEN/N/A@{ub}

  Gets palette information for @{i}pen.@{ui}  Returns pen number, red,
  green, and blue.

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}pen @{ui}- pen to return red, green, blue value for

  RESULTS
    @{i}result @{ui}- pen number and red, green, blue value

  SEE ALSO
    @{"Palette settings window" link MENU_PALETTE }, Preference command: @{"colors" link PREFS 104}

@{b}SetScreenPens PENS/M/A@{ub}

  Sets the screen pens.

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}pens @{ui}- list of screen pens

  RESULTS
    @{i}none @{ui}

  SEE ALSO
    @{"Palette settings window" link MENU_PALETTE }, Preference command: @{"spens" link PREFS 118}

@{b}GetScreenPens@{ub}

  Gets the screen pen list.

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}none @{ui}

  RESULTS
    @{i}result @{ui}- list of screen pens, "" if default pens

  SEE ALSO
    @{"Palette settings window" link MENU_PALETTE }, Preference command: @{"spens" link PREFS 118}

@{b}SetListviewPens PENS/M/A@{ub}

  Sets the listview pens.

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}pens @{ui}- list of listview pens, in the order: dirpen filepen selectpen

  RESULTS
    @{i}none @{ui}

  SEE ALSO
    @{"Listview settings window" link MENU_LISTVIEW}, Preference command: @{"lvpens" link PREFS 140}

@{b}GetListviewPens@{ub}

  Gets the listview pen list.

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}none @{ui}

  RESULTS
    @{i}result @{ui}- list of listview pens, in the order: dirpen filepen selectpen

  SEE ALSO
    @{"Listview settings window" link MENU_LISTVIEW}, Preference command: @{"lvpens" link PREFS 140}

@{b}SetScreenFont FONT/K/A,SIZE/N/A@{ub}

  Sets the screen font.

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}font @{ui}- font to use, including the .font extension
    @{i}size @{ui}- size of the font to use

  RESULTS
    @{i}none @{ui}

  SEE ALSO
    @{"ScreenMode settings window" link MENU_SCREENMODE}, Preference command: @{"screenfont" link PREFS 164}

@{b}GetScreenFont@{ub}

  Gets the screen font.

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}none @{ui}

  RESULTS
    @{i}result @{ui}- fontname and fontsize

  SEE ALSO
    @{"ScreenMode settings window" link MENU_SCREENMODE}, Preference command: @{"screenfont" link PREFS 164}

@{b}SetListviewFont FONT/K/A,SIZE/N/A@{ub}

  Sets the listview font.

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}font @{ui}- font to use, including the .font extension
    @{i}size @{ui}- size of the font to use

  RESULTS
    @{i}none @{ui}

  SEE ALSO
    @{"Listview settings window" link MENU_LISTVIEW}, Preference command: @{"lvfont" link PREFS 149}

@{b}GetListviewFont@{ub}

  Gets the listview font.

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}none @{ui}

  RESULTS
    @{i}result @{ui}- fontname and fontsize

  SEE ALSO
    @{"Listview settings window" link MENU_LISTVIEW}, Preference command: @{"lvfont" link PREFS 149}

@{b}SetPattern PATTERN/A@{ub}

  Sets the @{"pattern gadget" link PATTERN} to @{i}pattern@{ui}.

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}pattern @{ui}- string to set the pattern with

  RESULTS
    @{i}none @{ui}

  SEE ALSO
    @{"Pattern Gadget" link PATTERN}, Preference command: @{"pattern" link PREFS 213}

@{b}GetPattern@{ub}

  Gets the contents of the @{"pattern gadget" link PATTERN}.

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}none @{ui}

  RESULTS
    @{i}result @{ui}- contents of the @{"pattern gadget" link PATTERN}

  SEE ALSO
    @{"Pattern Gadget" link PATTERN}, Preference command: @{"pattern" link PREFS 213}

@{b}SetCopyOptions CLONEDATE/S,CLONEPROTECT/S,CLONECOMMENT/S,ASKOVER/S,UNSETARCH/S@{ub}

  Sets the copy and move options.

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}clonedate    @{ui}- clone date on copy/move
    @{i}cloneprotect @{ui}- clone protection bits on copy/move
    @{i}clonecomment @{ui}- clone comment on copy/move
    @{i}askover      @{ui}- ask to overwrite if destination exists
    @{i}unsetarch    @{ui}- unset archive bit when file is copied/moved

  RESULTS
    @{i}none @{ui}

  SEE ALSO
    @{"Copy/Move settings window" link COPYMOVE_OPTIONS }, Preference command: @{"copyoptions" link PREFS 195}

@{b}GetCopyOptions@{ub}

  Gets the copy options that are currently on.

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}none @{ui}

  RESULTS
    @{i}result @{ui}- string containing the copy options that are on,
             in the order: clonedate cloneprotect clonecomment askover
             unsetarch

  SEE ALSO
    @{"Copy/Move settings window" link COPYMOVE_OPTIONS }, Preference command: @{"copyoptions" link PREFS 195}

@{b}SetDeleteOptions ASK/S@{ub}

  Sets the delete options.

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}ask @{ui}- ask when deleting files are directories

  RESULTS
    @{i}none @{ui}

  SEE ALSO
    @{"Delete settings window" link DELETE_OPTIONS}, Preference command: @{"deleteoptions" link PREFS 181}

@{b}GetDeleteOptions@{ub}

  Get delete options that are currently on.

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}none @{ui}

  RESULTS
    @{i}result @{ui}- ASK if ask options is on, else nothing

  SEE ALSO
    @{"Delete settings window" link DELETE_OPTIONS}, Preference command: @{"deleteoptions" link PREFS 181}

@{b}SetProtectOptions PROTECTBITS@{ub}

  Sets the protection bits which are used by the @{"protect internal command" link INTERNALCMDS 116 }.

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}protectbits @{ui}- string containing: hsparwed

  RESULTS
    @{i}none @{ui}

  SEE ALSO
    @{"Protect settings window" link PROTECT_OPTIONS}, Preference command: @{"protectoptions" link PREFS 171}

@{b}GetProtectOptions@{ub}

  Get the currently set protection bits which are used by the
  @{"protect command" link INTERNALCMDS 116 }

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}none @{ui}

  RESULTS
    @{i}result @{ui}- string contianing which bits are on,
             includes: hsparwed

  SEE ALSO
    @{"Protect settings window" link PROTECT_OPTIONS}, Preference command: @{"protectoptions" link PREFS 171}

@{b}SetSort SORT/K/A,BY/K/A,WITH/K/A,SIDE@{ub}

  Sets the sort type for @{i}side.@{ui}  If @{i}side @{ui}is not
  specified, the active side will be effected.

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}sort @{ui}- ASCEND or DSCEND
    @{i}by   @{ui}- NAME, DATE, or SIZE
    @{i}with @{ui}- DIRSFIRST or DIRSMIXED
    @{i}side @{ui}- ACTIVE, LEFT, RIGHT, or OTHER

  RESULTS
    @{i}none @{ui}

  SEE ALSO
    @{"Listview settings window" link MENU_LISTVIEW}, @{"sort list" link CONCEPTS 6}, Preference command: @{"sortlist" link PREFS 285},
    @{"sortleft" link PREFS 221}, @{"sortright" link PREFS 221}

@{b}GetSort SIDE@{ub}

  Get the current sort type for @{i}side.@{ui}

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}side @{ui}- side to get information on: active, left, right, or
            other.

  RESULTS
    @{i}result @{ui}- string contain the current sort type,
             containing: [dscend | ascend] [name | date | size]
             [disfirst | dirsmixed]

  SEE ALSO
    @{"Listview settings window" link MENU_LISTVIEW}, @{"sort list" link CONCEPTS 6}, Preference command: @{"sortlist" link PREFS 285},
    @{"sortleft" link PREFS 221}, @{"sortright" link PREFS 221}

@{b}GetSelected@{ub}

  Get the next selected file or directory on the active side.

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}none @{ui}

  RESULTS
    @{i}result @{ui}- the next selected file or directory, if
             it is a directory it will end with a "/"

@{b}GetPubScreenName@{ub}

  Get the public screen name.

  ARGUMENTS
    @{i}none @{ui}

  RESULTS
    @{i}result @{ui}- the name of the public screen Rush is
             opened on or the public screen name of Rush

@endnode AREXX

